01Gn 11:18 When Peleg had lived 30 years, he became the father of Reu.
01Gn 11:19 And after he became the father of Reu, Peleg lived 209 years and had other sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:20 When Reu had lived 32 years, he became the father of Serug.
01Gn 11:21 And after he became the father of Serug, Reu lived 207 years and had other sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:22 When Serug had lived 30 years, he became the father of Nahor.
01Gn 11:23 And after he became the father of Nahor, Serug lived 200 years and had other sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:24 When Nahor had lived 29 years, he became the father of Terah.
01Gn 11:25 And after he became the father of Terah, Nahor lived 119 years and had other sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:26 After Terah had lived 70 years, he became the father of Abram, Nahor and Haran.
01Gn 11:27 This is the account of Terah. Terah became the father of Abram, Nahor and Haran. And Haran became the father of Lot.
01Gn 11:28 While his father Terah was still alive, Haran died in Ur of the Chaldeans, in the land of his birth.
01Gn 11:29 Abram and Nahor both married. The name of Abram's wife was Sarai, and the name of Nahor's wife was Milcah; she was the daughter of Haran, the father of both Milcah and Iscah.
01Gn 11:30 Now Sarai was barren; she had no children.
01Gn 11:31 Terah took his son Abram, his grandson Lot son of Haran, and his daughter-in-law Sarai, the wife of his son Abram, and together they set out from Ur of the Chaldeans to go to Canaan. But when they came to Haran, they settled there.
01Gn 11:32 Terah lived 205 years, and he died in Haran.
01Gn 12:1 The LORD had said to Abram, "Leave your country, your people and your father's household and go to the land I will show you.
01Gn 12:2 "I will make you into a great nation and I will bless you; I will make your name great, and you will be a blessing.
01Gn 12:3 I will bless those who bless you, and whoever curses you I will curse; and all peoples on earth will be blessed through you."
01Gn 12:4 So Abram left, as the LORD had told him; and Lot went with him. Abram was seventy-five years old when he set out from Haran.
