01Gn 15:17 When the sun had set and darkness had fallen, a smoking firepot with a blazing torch appeared and passed between the pieces.
01Gn 15:18 On that day the LORD made a covenant with Abram and said, "To your descendants I give this land, from the river of Egypt to the great river, the Euphrates--
01Gn 15:19 the land of the Kenites, Kenizzites, Kadmonites,
01Gn 15:20 Hittites, Perizzites, Rephaites,
01Gn 15:21 Amorites, Canaanites, Girgashites and Jebusites."
01Gn 16:1 Now Sarai, Abram's wife, had borne him no children. But she had an Egyptian maidservant named Hagar;
01Gn 16:2 so she said to Abram, "The LORD has kept me from having children. Go, sleep with my maidservant; perhaps I can build a family through her." Abram agreed to what Sarai said.
01Gn 16:3 So after Abram had been living in Canaan ten years, Sarai his wife took her Egyptian maidservant Hagar and gave her to her husband to be his wife.
01Gn 16:4 He slept with Hagar, and she conceived. When she knew she was pregnant, she began to despise her mistress.
01Gn 16:5 Then Sarai said to Abram, "You are responsible for the wrong I am suffering. I put my servant in your arms, and now that she knows she is pregnant, she despises me. May the LORD judge between you and me."
01Gn 16:6 "Your servant is in your hands," Abram said. "Do with her whatever you think best." Then Sarai mistreated Hagar; so she fled from her.
01Gn 16:7 The angel of the LORD found Hagar near a spring in the desert; it was the spring that is beside the road to Shur.
01Gn 16:8 And he said, "Hagar, servant of Sarai, where have you come from, and where are you going?" "I'm running away from my mistress Sarai," she answered.
01Gn 16:9 Then the angel of the LORD told her, "Go back to your mistress and submit to her."
01Gn 16:10 The angel added, "I will so increase your descendants that they will be too numerous to count."
01Gn 16:11 The angel of the LORD also said to her£º "You are now with child and you will have a son. You shall name him Ishmael, for the LORD has heard of your misery.
01Gn 16:12 He will be a wild donkey of a man; his hand will be against everyone and everyone's hand against him, and he will live in hostility toward all his brothers."
01Gn 16:13 She gave this name to the LORD who spoke to her£º "You are the God who sees me," for she said, "I have now seen the One who sees me."
01Gn 16:14 That is why the well was called Beer Lahai Roi; it is still there, between Kadesh and Bered.
01Gn 16:15 So Hagar bore Abram a son, and Abram gave the name Ishmael to the son she had borne.
01Gn 16:16 Abram was eighty-six years old when Hagar bore him Ishmael.
01Gn 17:1 When Abram was ninety-nine years old, the LORD appeared to him and said, "I am God Almighty; walk before me and be blameless.
01Gn 17:2 I will confirm my covenant between me and you and will greatly increase your numbers."
01Gn 17:3 Abram fell facedown, and God said to him,
01Gn 17:4 "As for me, this is my covenant with you£º You will be the father of many nations.
01Gn 17:5 No longer will you be called Abram; your name will be Abraham, for I have made you a father of many nations.
01Gn 17:6 I will make you very fruitful; I will make nations of you, and kings will come from you.
01Gn 17:7 I will establish my covenant as an everlasting covenant between me and you and your descendants after you for the generations to come, to be your God and the God of your descendants after you.
01Gn 17:8 The whole land of Canaan, where you are now an alien, I will give as an everlasting possession to you and your descendants after you; and I will be their God."
01Gn 17:9 Then God said to Abraham, "As for you, you must keep my covenant, you and your descendants after you for the generations to come.
01Gn 17:10 This is my covenant with you and your descendants after you, the covenant you are to keep£º Every male among you shall be circumcised.
01Gn 17:11 You are to undergo circumcision, and it will be the sign of the covenant between me and you.
01Gn 17:12 For the generations to come every male among you who is eight days old must be circumcised, including those born in your household or bought with money from a foreigner--those who are not your offspring.
01Gn 17:13 Whether born in your household or bought with your money, they must be circumcised. My covenant in your flesh is to be an everlasting covenant.
01Gn 17:14 Any uncircumcised male, who has not been circumcised in the flesh, will be cut off from his people; he has broken my covenant."
01Gn 17:15 God also said to Abraham, "As for Sarai your wife, you are no longer to call her Sarai; her name will be Sarah.
01Gn 17:16 I will bless her and will surely give you a son by her. I will bless her so that she will be the mother of nations; kings of peoples will come from her."
01Gn 17:17 Abraham fell facedown; he laughed and said to himself, "Will a son be born to a man a hundred years old? Will Sarah bear a child at the age of ninety?"
01Gn 17:18 And Abraham said to God, "If only Ishmael might live under your blessing!"
01Gn 17:19 Then God said, "Yes, but your wife Sarah will bear you a son, and you will call him Isaac. I will establish my covenant with him as an everlasting covenant for his descendants after him.
01Gn 17:20 And as for Ishmael, I have heard you£º I will surely bless him; I will make him fruitful and will greatly increase his numbers. He will be the father of twelve rulers, and I will make him into a great nation.
01Gn 17:21 But my covenant I will establish with Isaac, whom Sarah will bear to you by this time next year."
01Gn 17:22 When he had finished speaking with Abraham, God went up from him.
01Gn 17:23 On that very day Abraham took his son Ishmael and all those born in his household or bought with his money, every male in his household, and circumcised them, as God told him.
01Gn 17:24 Abraham was ninety-nine years old when he was circumcised,
01Gn 17:25 and his son Ishmael was thirteen;
01Gn 17:26 Abraham and his son Ishmael were both circumcised on that same day.
01Gn 17:27 And every male in Abraham's household, including those born in his household or bought from a foreigner, was circumcised with him.
01Gn 18:1 The LORD appeared to Abraham near the great trees of Mamre while he was sitting at the entrance to his tent in the heat of the day.
01Gn 18:2 Abraham looked up and saw three men standing nearby. When he saw them, he hurried from the entrance of his tent to meet them and bowed low to the ground.
01Gn 18:3 He said, "If I have found favor in your eyes, my lord, do not pass your servant by.
01Gn 18:4 Let a little water be brought, and then you may all wash your feet and rest under this tree.
01Gn 18:5 Let me get you something to eat, so you can be refreshed and then go on your way--now that you have come to your servant." "Very well," they answered, "do as you say."
01Gn 18:6 So Abraham hurried into the tent to Sarah. "Quick," he said, "get three seahs of fine flour and knead it and bake some bread."
01Gn 18:7 Then he ran to the herd and selected a choice, tender calf and gave it to a servant, who hurried to prepare it.
01Gn 18:8 He then brought some curds and milk and the calf that had been prepared, and set these before them. While they ate, he stood near them under a tree.
01Gn 18:9 "Where is your wife Sarah?" they asked him. "There, in the tent," he said.
01Gn 18:10 Then the LORD said, "I will surely return to you about this time next year, and Sarah your wife will have a son." Now Sarah was listening at the entrance to the tent, which was behind him.
01Gn 18:11 Abraham and Sarah were already old and well advanced in years, and Sarah was past the age of childbearing.
01Gn 18:12 So Sarah laughed to herself as she thought, "After I am worn out and my master is old, will I now have this pleasure?"
01Gn 18:13 Then the LORD said to Abraham, "Why did Sarah laugh and say, 'Will I really have a child, now that I am old?'
01Gn 18:14 Is anything too hard for the LORD? I will return to you at the appointed time next year and Sarah will have a son."
01Gn 18:15 Sarah was afraid, so she lied and said, "I did not laugh." But he said, "Yes, you did laugh."
01Gn 18:16 When the men got up to leave, they looked down toward Sodom, and Abraham walked along with them to see them on their way.
01Gn 18:17 Then the LORD said, "Shall I hide from Abraham what I am about to do?
01Gn 18:18 Abraham will surely become a great and powerful nation, and all nations on earth will be blessed through him.
01Gn 18:19 For I have chosen him, so that he will direct his children and his household after him to keep the way of the LORD by doing what is right and just, so that the LORD will bring about for Abraham what he has promised him."
01Gn 18:20 Then the LORD said, "The outcry against Sodom and Gomorrah is so great and their sin so grievous
01Gn 18:21 that I will go down and see if what they have done is as bad as the outcry that has reached me. If not, I will know."
01Gn 18:22 The men turned away and went toward Sodom, but Abraham remained standing before the LORD.
01Gn 18:23 Then Abraham approached him and said£º "Will you sweep away the righteous with the wicked?
01Gn 18:24 What if there are fifty righteous people in the city? Will you really sweep it away and not spare the place for the sake of the fifty righteous people in it?
01Gn 18:25 Far be it from you to do such a thing--to kill the righteous with the wicked, treating the righteous and the wicked alike. Far be it from you! Will not the Judge of all the earth do right?"
01Gn 18:26 The LORD said, "If I find fifty righteous people in the city of Sodom, I will spare the whole place for their sake."
01Gn 18:27 Then Abraham spoke up again£º "Now that I have been so bold as to speak to the Lord, though I am nothing but dust and ashes,
01Gn 18:28 what if the number of the righteous is five less than fifty? Will you destroy the whole city because of five people?" "If I find forty-five there," he said, "I will not destroy it."
01Gn 18:29 Once again he spoke to him, "What if only forty are found there?" He said, "For the sake of forty, I will not do it."
01Gn 18:30 Then he said, "May the Lord not be angry, but let me speak. What if only thirty can be found there?" He answered, "I will not do it if I find thirty there."
01Gn 18:31 Abraham said, "Now that I have been so bold as to speak to the Lord, what if only twenty can be found there?" He said, "For the sake of twenty, I will not destroy it."
01Gn 18:32 Then he said, "May the Lord not be angry, but let me speak just once more. What if only ten can be found there?" He answered, "For the sake of ten, I will not destroy it."
01Gn 18:33 When the LORD had finished speaking with Abraham, he left, and Abraham returned home.
01Gn 19:1 The two angels arrived at Sodom in the evening, and Lot was sitting in the gateway of the city. When he saw them, he got up to meet them and bowed down with his face to the ground.
01Gn 19:2 "My lords," he said, "please turn aside to your servant's house. You can wash your feet and spend the night and then go on your way early in the morning." "No," they answered, "we will spend the night in the square."
01Gn 19:3 But he insisted so strongly that they did go with him and entered his house. He prepared a meal for them, baking bread without yeast, and they ate.
01Gn 19:4 Before they had gone to bed, all the men from every part of the city of Sodom--both young and old--surrounded the house.
01Gn 19:5 They called to Lot, "Where are the men who came to you tonight? Bring them out to us so that we can have sex with them."
01Gn 19:6 Lot went outside to meet them and shut the door behind him
01Gn 19:7 and said, "No, my friends. Don't do this wicked thing.
01Gn 19:8 Look, I have two daughters who have never slept with a man. Let me bring them out to you, and you can do what you like with them. But don't do anything to these men, for they have come under the protection of my roof."
01Gn 19:9 "Get out of our way," they replied. And they said, "This fellow came here as an alien, and now he wants to play the judge! We'll treat you worse than them." They kept bringing pressure on Lot and moved forward to break down the door.
01Gn 19:10 But the men inside reached out and pulled Lot back into the house and shut the door.
01Gn 19:11 Then they struck the men who were at the door of the house, young and old, with blindness so that they could not find the door.
01Gn 19:12 The two men said to Lot, "Do you have anyone else here--sons-in-law, sons or daughters, or anyone else in the city who belongs to you? Get them out of here,
01Gn 19:13 because we are going to destroy this place. The outcry to the LORD against its people is so great that he has sent us to destroy it."
01Gn 19:14 So Lot went out and spoke to his sons-in-law, who were pledged to marry his daughters. He said, "Hurry and get out of this place, because the LORD is about to destroy the city!" But his sons-in-law thought he was joking.
01Gn 19:15 With the coming of dawn, the angels urged Lot, saying, "Hurry! Take your wife and your two daughters who are here, or you will be swept away when the city is punished."
01Gn 19:16 When he hesitated, the men grasped his hand and the hands of his wife and of his two daughters and led them safely out of the city, for the LORD was merciful to them.
01Gn 19:17 As soon as they had brought them out, one of them said, "Flee for your lives! Don't look back, and don't stop anywhere in the plain! Flee to the mountains or you will be swept away!"
01Gn 19:18 But Lot said to them, "No, my lords, please!
01Gn 19:19 Your servant has found favor in your eyes, and you have shown great kindness to me in sparing my life. But I can't flee to the mountains; this disaster will overtake me, and I'll die.
01Gn 19:20 Look, here is a town near enough to run to, and it is small. Let me flee to it--it is very small, isn't it? Then my life will be spared."
01Gn 19:21 He said to him, "Very well, I will grant this request too; I will not overthrow the town you speak of.
01Gn 19:22 But flee there quickly, because I cannot do anything until you reach it." (That is why the town was called Zoar.)
01Gn 19:23 By the time Lot reached Zoar, the sun had risen over the land.
01Gn 19:24 Then the LORD rained down burning sulfur on Sodom and Gomorrah--from the LORD out of the heavens.
01Gn 19:25 Thus he overthrew those cities and the entire plain, including all those living in the cities--and also the vegetation in the land.
01Gn 19:26 But Lot's wife looked back, and she became a pillar of salt.
01Gn 19:27 Early the next morning Abraham got up and returned to the place where he had stood before the LORD.
01Gn 19:28 He looked down toward Sodom and Gomorrah, toward all the land of the plain, and he saw dense smoke rising from the land, like smoke from a furnace.
01Gn 19:29 So when God destroyed the cities of the plain, he remembered Abraham, and he brought Lot out of the catastrophe that overthrew the cities where Lot had lived.
01Gn 19:30 Lot and his two daughters left Zoar and settled in the mountains, for he was afraid to stay in Zoar. He and his two daughters lived in a cave.
01Gn 19:31 One day the older daughter said to the younger, "Our father is old, and there is no man around here to lie with us, as is the custom all over the earth.
01Gn 19:32 Let's get our father to drink wine and then lie with him and preserve our family line through our father."
01Gn 19:33 That night they got their father to drink wine, and the older daughter went in and lay with him. He was not aware of it when she lay down or when she got up.
01Gn 19:34 The next day the older daughter said to the younger, "Last night I lay with my father. Let's get him to drink wine again tonight, and you go in and lie with him so we can preserve our family line through our father."
01Gn 19:35 So they got their father to drink wine that night also, and the younger daughter went and lay with him. Again he was not aware of it when she lay down or when she got up.
01Gn 19:36 So both of Lot's daughters became pregnant by their father.
01Gn 19:37 The older daughter had a son, and she named him Moab; he is the father of the Moabites of today.
01Gn 19:38 The younger daughter also had a son, and she named him Ben-Ammi; he is the father of the Ammonites of today.
01Gn 20:1 Now Abraham moved on from there into the region of the Negev and lived between Kadesh and Shur. For a while he stayed in Gerar,
01Gn 20:2 and there Abraham said of his wife Sarah, "She is my sister." Then Abimelech king of Gerar sent for Sarah and took her.
01Gn 20:3 But God came to Abimelech in a dream one night and said to him, "You are as good as dead because of the woman you have taken; she is a married woman."
01Gn 20:4 Now Abimelech had not gone near her, so he said, "Lord, will you destroy an innocent nation?
01Gn 20:5 Did he not say to me, 'She is my sister,' and didn't she also say, 'He is my brother'? I have done this with a clear conscience and clean hands."
01Gn 20:6 Then God said to him in the dream, "Yes, I know you did this with a clear conscience, and so I have kept you from sinning against me. That is why I did not let you touch her.
01Gn 20:7 Now return the man's wife, for he is a prophet, and he will pray for you and you will live. But if you do not return her, you may be sure that you and all yours will die."
01Gn 20:8 Early the next morning Abimelech summoned all his officials, and when he told them all that had happened, they were very much afraid.
01Gn 20:9 Then Abimelech called Abraham in and said, "What have you done to us? How have I wronged you that you have brought such great guilt upon me and my kingdom? You have done things to me that should not be done."
01Gn 20:10 And Abimelech asked Abraham, "What was your reason for doing this?"
01Gn 20:11 Abraham replied, "I said to myself, 'There is surely no fear of God in this place, and they will kill me because of my wife.'
01Gn 20:12 Besides, she really is my sister, the daughter of my father though not of my mother; and she became my wife.
01Gn 20:13 And when God had me wander from my father's household, I said to her, 'This is how you can show your love to me£º Everywhere we go, say of me, "He is my brother." '"
01Gn 20:14 Then Abimelech brought sheep and cattle and male and female slaves and gave them to Abraham, and he returned Sarah his wife to him.
01Gn 20:15 And Abimelech said, "My land is before you; live wherever you like."
01Gn 20:16 To Sarah he said, "I am giving your brother a thousand shekels of silver. This is to cover the offense against you before all who are with you; you are completely vindicated."
01Gn 20:17 Then Abraham prayed to God, and God healed Abimelech, his wife and his slave girls so they could have children again,
01Gn 20:18 for the LORD had closed up every womb in Abimelech's household because of Abraham's wife Sarah.
01Gn 21:1 Now the LORD was gracious to Sarah as he had said, and the LORD did for Sarah what he had promised.
01Gn 21:2 Sarah became pregnant and bore a son to Abraham in his old age, at the very time God had promised him.
01Gn 21:3 Abraham gave the name Isaac to the son Sarah bore him.
01Gn 21:4 When his son Isaac was eight days old, Abraham circumcised him, as God commanded him.
01Gn 21:5 Abraham was a hundred years old when his son Isaac was born to him.
01Gn 21:6 Sarah said, "God has brought me laughter, and everyone who hears about this will laugh with me."
01Gn 21:7 And she added, "Who would have said to Abraham that Sarah would nurse children? Yet I have borne him a son in his old age."
01Gn 21:8 The child grew and was weaned, and on the day Isaac was weaned Abraham held a great feast.
01Gn 21:9 But Sarah saw that the son whom Hagar the Egyptian had borne to Abraham was mocking,
01Gn 21:10 and she said to Abraham, "Get rid of that slave woman and her son, for that slave woman's son will never share in the inheritance with my son Isaac."
01Gn 21:11 The matter distressed Abraham greatly because it concerned his son.
01Gn 21:12 But God said to him, "Do not be so distressed about the boy and your maidservant. Listen to whatever Sarah tells you, because it is through Isaac that your offspring will be reckoned.
01Gn 21:13 I will make the son of the maidservant into a nation also, because he is your offspring."
01Gn 21:14 Early the next morning Abraham took some food and a skin of water and gave them to Hagar. He set them on her shoulders and then sent her off with the boy. She went on her way and wandered in the desert of Beersheba.
01Gn 21:15 When the water in the skin was gone, she put the boy under one of the bushes.
01Gn 21:16 Then she went off and sat down nearby, about a bowshot away, for she thought, "I cannot watch the boy die." And as she sat there nearby, she began to sob.
01Gn 21:17 God heard the boy crying, and the angel of God called to Hagar from heaven and said to her, "What is the matter, Hagar? Do not be afraid; God has heard the boy crying as he lies there.
01Gn 21:18 Lift the boy up and take him by the hand, for I will make him into a great nation."
01Gn 21:19 Then God opened her eyes and she saw a well of water. So she went and filled the skin with water and gave the boy a drink.
01Gn 21:20 God was with the boy as he grew up. He lived in the desert and became an archer.
01Gn 21:21 While he was living in the Desert of Paran, his mother got a wife for him from Egypt.
01Gn 21:22 At that time Abimelech and Phicol the commander of his forces said to Abraham, "God is with you in everything you do.
01Gn 21:23 Now swear to me here before God that you will not deal falsely with me or my children or my descendants. Show to me and the country where you are living as an alien the same kindness I have shown to you."
01Gn 21:24 Abraham said, "I swear it."
01Gn 21:25 Then Abraham complained to Abimelech about a well of water that Abimelech's servants had seized.
01Gn 21:26 But Abimelech said, "I don't know who has done this. You did not tell me, and I heard about it only today."
01Gn 21:27 So Abraham brought sheep and cattle and gave them to Abimelech, and the two men made a treaty.
01Gn 21:28 Abraham set apart seven ewe lambs from the flock,
01Gn 21:29 and Abimelech asked Abraham, "What is the meaning of these seven ewe lambs you have set apart by themselves?"
01Gn 21:30 He replied, "Accept these seven lambs from my hand as a witness that I dug this well."
01Gn 21:31 So that place was called Beersheba, because the two men swore an oath there.
01Gn 21:32 After the treaty had been made at Beersheba, Abimelech and Phicol the commander of his forces returned to the land of the Philistines.
01Gn 21:33 Abraham planted a tamarisk tree in Beersheba, and there he called upon the name of the LORD, the Eternal God.
01Gn 21:34 And Abraham stayed in the land of the Philistines for a long time.
01Gn 22:1 Some time later God tested Abraham. He said to him, "Abraham!" "Here I am," he replied.
01Gn 22:2 Then God said, "Take your son, your only son, Isaac, whom you love, and go to the region of Moriah. Sacrifice him there as a burnt offering on one of the mountains I will tell you about."
01Gn 22:3 Early the next morning Abraham got up and saddled his donkey. He took with him two of his servants and his son Isaac. When he had cut enough wood for the burnt offering, he set out for the place God had told him about.
01Gn 22:4 On the third day Abraham looked up and saw the place in the distance.
01Gn 22:5 He said to his servants, "Stay here with the donkey while I and the boy go over there. We will worship and then we will come back to you."
01Gn 22:6 Abraham took the wood for the burnt offering and placed it on his son Isaac, and he himself carried the fire and the knife. As the two of them went on together,
01Gn 22:7 Isaac spoke up and said to his father Abraham, "Father?" "Yes, my son?" Abraham replied. "The fire and wood are here," Isaac said, "but where is the lamb for the burnt offering?"
01Gn 22:8 Abraham answered, "God himself will provide the lamb for the burnt offering, my son." And the two of them went on together.
01Gn 22:9 When they reached the place God had told him about, Abraham built an altar there and arranged the wood on it. He bound his son Isaac and laid him on the altar, on top of the wood.
01Gn 22:10 Then he reached out his hand and took the knife to slay his son.
01Gn 22:11 But the angel of the LORD called out to him from heaven, "Abraham! Abraham!" "Here I am," he replied.
01Gn 22:12 "Do not lay a hand on the boy," he said. "Do not do anything to him. Now I know that you fear God, because you have not withheld from me your son, your only son."
01Gn 22:13 Abraham looked up and there in a thicket he saw a ram caught by its horns. He went over and took the ram and sacrificed it as a burnt offering instead of his son.
01Gn 22:14 So Abraham called that place The LORD Will Provide. And to this day it is said, "On the mountain of the LORD it will be provided."
01Gn 22:15 The angel of the LORD called to Abraham from heaven a second time
01Gn 22:16 and said, "I swear by myself, declares the LORD, that because you have done this and have not withheld your son, your only son,
01Gn 22:17 I will surely bless you and make your descendants as numerous as the stars in the sky and as the sand on the seashore. Your descendants will take possession of the cities of their enemies,
01Gn 22:18 and through your offspring all nations on earth will be blessed, because you have obeyed me."
01Gn 22:19 Then Abraham returned to his servants, and they set off together for Beersheba. And Abraham stayed in Beersheba.
01Gn 22:20 Some time later Abraham was told, "Milcah is also a mother; she has borne sons to your brother Nahor£º
01Gn 22:21 Uz the firstborn, Buz his brother, Kemuel (the father of Aram),
01Gn 22:22 Kesed, Hazo, Pildash, Jidlaph and Bethuel."
01Gn 22:23 Bethuel became the father of Rebekah. Milcah bore these eight sons to Abraham's brother Nahor.
01Gn 22:24 His concubine, whose name was Reumah, also had sons£º Tebah, Gaham, Tahash and Maacah.
01Gn 23:1 Sarah lived to be a hundred and twenty-seven years old.
01Gn 23:2 She died at Kiriath Arba (that is, Hebron) in the land of Canaan, and Abraham went to mourn for Sarah and to weep over her.
01Gn 23:3 Then Abraham rose from beside his dead wife and spoke to the Hittites. He said,
01Gn 23:4 "I am an alien and a stranger among you. Sell me some property for a burial site here so I can bury my dead."
01Gn 23:5 The Hittites replied to Abraham,
01Gn 23:6 "Sir, listen to us. You are a mighty prince among us. Bury your dead in the choicest of our tombs. None of us will refuse you his tomb for burying your dead."
01Gn 23:7 Then Abraham rose and bowed down before the people of the land, the Hittites.
01Gn 23:8 He said to them, "If you are willing to let me bury my dead, then listen to me and intercede with Ephron son of Zohar on my behalf
01Gn 23:9 so he will sell me the cave of Machpelah, which belongs to him and is at the end of his field. Ask him to sell it to me for the full price as a burial site among you."
01Gn 23:10 Ephron the Hittite was sitting among his people and he replied to Abraham in the hearing of all the Hittites who had come to the gate of his city.
01Gn 23:11 "No, my lord," he said. "Listen to me; I give you the field, and I give you the cave that is in it. I give it to you in the presence of my people. Bury your dead."
01Gn 23:12 Again Abraham bowed down before the people of the land
01Gn 23:13 and he said to Ephron in their hearing, "Listen to me, if you will. I will pay the price of the field. Accept it from me so I can bury my dead there."
01Gn 23:14 Ephron answered Abraham,
01Gn 23:15 "Listen to me, my lord; the land is worth four hundred shekels of silver, but what is that between me and you? Bury your dead."
01Gn 23:16 Abraham agreed to Ephron's terms and weighed out for him the price he had named in the hearing of the Hittites£º four hundred shekels of silver, according to the weight current among the merchants.
01Gn 23:17 So Ephron's field in Machpelah near Mamre--both the field and the cave in it, and all the trees within the borders of the field--was deeded
01Gn 23:18 to Abraham as his property in the presence of all the Hittites who had come to the gate of the city.
01Gn 23:19 Afterward Abraham buried his wife Sarah in the cave in the field of Machpelah near Mamre (which is at Hebron) in the land of Canaan.
01Gn 23:20 So the field and the cave in it were deeded to Abraham by the Hittites as a burial site.
01Gn 24:1 Abraham was now old and well advanced in years, and the LORD had blessed him in every way.
01Gn 24:2 He said to the chief servant in his household, the one in charge of all that he had, "Put your hand under my thigh.
01Gn 24:3 I want you to swear by the LORD, the God of heaven and the God of earth, that you will not get a wife for my son from the daughters of the Canaanites, among whom I am living,
01Gn 24:4 but will go to my country and my own relatives and get a wife for my son Isaac."
01Gn 24:5 The servant asked him, "What if the woman is unwilling to come back with me to this land? Shall I then take your son back to the country you came from?"
01Gn 24:6 "Make sure that you do not take my son back there," Abraham said.
01Gn 24:7 "The LORD, the God of heaven, who brought me out of my father's household and my native land and who spoke to me and promised me on oath, saying, 'To your offspring I will give this land'--he will send his angel before you so that you can get a wife for my son from there.
01Gn 24:8 If the woman is unwilling to come back with you, then you will be released from this oath of mine. Only do not take my son back there."
01Gn 24:9 So the servant put his hand under the thigh of his master Abraham and swore an oath to him concerning this matter.
01Gn 24:10 Then the servant took ten of his master's camels and left, taking with him all kinds of good things from his master. He set out for Aram Naharaim and made his way to the town of Nahor.
01Gn 24:11 He had the camels kneel down near the well outside the town; it was toward evening, the time the women go out to draw water.
01Gn 24:12 Then he prayed, "O LORD, God of my master Abraham, give me success today, and show kindness to my master Abraham.
01Gn 24:13 See, I am standing beside this spring, and the daughters of the townspeople are coming out to draw water.
01Gn 24:14 May it be that when I say to a girl, 'Please let down your jar that I may have a drink,' and she says, 'Drink, and I'll water your camels too'--let her be the one you have chosen for your servant Isaac. By this I will know that you have shown kindness to my master."
01Gn 24:15 Before he had finished praying, Rebekah came out with her jar on her shoulder. She was the daughter of Bethuel son of Milcah, who was the wife of Abraham's brother Nahor.
01Gn 24:16 The girl was very beautiful, a virgin; no man had ever lain with her. She went down to the spring, filled her jar and came up again.
01Gn 24:17 The servant hurried to meet her and said, "Please give me a little water from your jar."
01Gn 24:18 "Drink, my lord," she said, and quickly lowered the jar to her hands and gave him a drink.
01Gn 24:19 After she had given him a drink, she said, "I'll draw water for your camels too, until they have finished drinking."
01Gn 24:20 So she quickly emptied her jar into the trough, ran back to the well to draw more water, and drew enough for all his camels.
01Gn 24:21 Without saying a word, the man watched her closely to learn whether or not the LORD had made his journey successful.
01Gn 24:22 When the camels had finished drinking, the man took out a gold nose ring weighing a beka and two gold bracelets weighing ten shekels.
01Gn 24:23 Then he asked, "Whose daughter are you? Please tell me, is there room in your father's house for us to spend the night?"
01Gn 24:24 She answered him, "I am the daughter of Bethuel, the son that Milcah bore to Nahor."
01Gn 24:25 And she added, "We have plenty of straw and fodder, as well as room for you to spend the night."
01Gn 24:26 Then the man bowed down and worshiped the LORD,
01Gn 24:27 saying, "Praise be to the LORD, the God of my master Abraham, who has not abandoned his kindness and faithfulness to my master. As for me, the LORD has led me on the journey to the house of my master's relatives."
01Gn 24:28 The girl ran and told her mother's household about these things.
01Gn 24:29 Now Rebekah had a brother named Laban, and he hurried out to the man at the spring.
01Gn 24:30 As soon as he had seen the nose ring, and the bracelets on his sister's arms, and had heard Rebekah tell what the man said to her, he went out to the man and found him standing by the camels near the spring.
01Gn 24:31 "Come, you who are blessed by the LORD," he said. "Why are you standing out here? I have prepared the house and a place for the camels."
01Gn 24:32 So the man went to the house, and the camels were unloaded. Straw and fodder were brought for the camels, and water for him and his men to wash their feet.
01Gn 24:33 Then food was set before him, but he said, "I will not eat until I have told you what I have to say." "Then tell us," Laban said.
01Gn 24:34 So he said, "I am Abraham's servant.
01Gn 24:35 The LORD has blessed my master abundantly, and he has become wealthy. He has given him sheep and cattle, silver and gold, menservants and maidservants, and camels and donkeys.
01Gn 24:36 My master's wife Sarah has borne him a son in her old age, and he has given him everything he owns.
01Gn 24:37 And my master made me swear an oath, and said, 'You must not get a wife for my son from the daughters of the Canaanites, in whose land I live,
01Gn 24:38 but go to my father's family and to my own clan, and get a wife for my son.'
01Gn 24:39 "Then I asked my master, 'What if the woman will not come back with me?'
01Gn 24:40 "He replied, 'The LORD, before whom I have walked, will send his angel with you and make your journey a success, so that you can get a wife for my son from my own clan and from my father's family.
01Gn 24:41 Then, when you go to my clan, you will be released from my oath even if they refuse to give her to you--you will be released from my oath.'
01Gn 24:42 "When I came to the spring today, I said, 'O LORD, God of my master Abraham, if you will, please grant success to the journey on which I have come.
01Gn 24:43 See, I am standing beside this spring; if a maiden comes out to draw water and I say to her, "Please let me drink a little water from your jar,"
01Gn 24:44 and if she says to me, "Drink, and I'll draw water for your camels too," let her be the one the LORD has chosen for my master's son.'
01Gn 24:45 "Before I finished praying in my heart, Rebekah came out, with her jar on her shoulder. She went down to the spring and drew water, and I said to her, 'Please give me a drink.'
01Gn 24:46 "She quickly lowered her jar from her shoulder and said, 'Drink, and I'll water your camels too.' So I drank, and she watered the camels also.
01Gn 24:47 "I asked her, 'Whose daughter are you?' "She said, 'The daughter of Bethuel son of Nahor, whom Milcah bore to him.' "Then I put the ring in her nose and the bracelets on her arms,
01Gn 24:48 and I bowed down and worshiped the LORD. I praised the LORD, the God of my master Abraham, who had led me on the right road to get the granddaughter of my master's brother for his son.
01Gn 24:49 Now if you will show kindness and faithfulness to my master, tell me; and if not, tell me, so I may know which way to turn."
01Gn 24:50 Laban and Bethuel answered, "This is from the LORD; we can say nothing to you one way or the other.
01Gn 24:51 Here is Rebekah; take her and go, and let her become the wife of your master's son, as the LORD has directed."
01Gn 24:52 When Abraham's servant heard what they said, he bowed down to the ground before the LORD.
01Gn 24:53 Then the servant brought out gold and silver jewelry and articles of clothing and gave them to Rebekah; he also gave costly gifts to her brother and to her mother.
01Gn 24:54 Then he and the men who were with him ate and drank and spent the night there. When they got up the next morning, he said, "Send me on my way to my master."
01Gn 24:55 But her brother and her mother replied, "Let the girl remain with us ten days or so; then you may go."
01Gn 24:56 But he said to them, "Do not detain me, now that the LORD has granted success to my journey. Send me on my way so I may go to my master."
01Gn 24:57 Then they said, "Let's call the girl and ask her about it."
01Gn 24:58 So they called Rebekah and asked her, "Will you go with this man?" "I will go," she said.
01Gn 24:59 So they sent their sister Rebekah on her way, along with her nurse and Abraham's servant and his men.
01Gn 24:60 And they blessed Rebekah and said to her, "Our sister, may you increase to thousands upon thousands; may your offspring possess the gates of their enemies."
01Gn 24:61 Then Rebekah and her maids got ready and mounted their camels and went back with the man. So the servant took Rebekah and left.
01Gn 24:62 Now Isaac had come from Beer Lahai Roi, for he was living in the Negev.
01Gn 24:63 He went out to the field one evening to meditate, and as he looked up, he saw camels approaching.
01Gn 24:64 Rebekah also looked up and saw Isaac. She got down from her camel
01Gn 24:65 and asked the servant, "Who is that man in the field coming to meet us?" "He is my master," the servant answered. So she took her veil and covered herself.
01Gn 24:66 Then the servant told Isaac all he had done.
01Gn 24:67 Isaac brought her into the tent of his mother Sarah, and he married Rebekah. So she became his wife, and he loved her; and Isaac was comforted after his mother's death.
01Gn 25:1 Abraham took another wife, whose name was Keturah.
01Gn 25:2 She bore him Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak and Shuah.
01Gn 25:3 Jokshan was the father of Sheba and Dedan; the descendants of Dedan were the Asshurites, the Letushites and the Leummites.
01Gn 25:4 The sons of Midian were Ephah, Epher, Hanoch, Abida and Eldaah. All these were descendants of Keturah.
01Gn 25:5 Abraham left everything he owned to Isaac.
01Gn 25:6 But while he was still living, he gave gifts to the sons of his concubines and sent them away from his son Isaac to the land of the east.
01Gn 25:7 Altogether, Abraham lived a hundred and seventy-five years.
01Gn 25:8 Then Abraham breathed his last and died at a good old age, an old man and full of years; and he was gathered to his people.
01Gn 25:9 His sons Isaac and Ishmael buried him in the cave of Machpelah near Mamre, in the field of Ephron son of Zohar the Hittite,
01Gn 25:10 the field Abraham had bought from the Hittites. There Abraham was buried with his wife Sarah.
01Gn 25:11 After Abraham's death, God blessed his son Isaac, who then lived near Beer Lahai Roi.
01Gn 25:12 This is the account of Abraham's son Ishmael, whom Sarah's maidservant, Hagar the Egyptian, bore to Abraham.
01Gn 25:13 These are the names of the sons of Ishmael, listed in the order of their birth£º Nebaioth the firstborn of Ishmael, Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam,
01Gn 25:14 Mishma, Dumah, Massa,
01Gn 25:15 Hadad, Tema, Jetur, Naphish and Kedemah.
01Gn 25:16 These were the sons of Ishmael, and these are the names of the twelve tribal rulers according to their settlements and camps.
01Gn 25:17 Altogether, Ishmael lived a hundred and thirty-seven years. He breathed his last and died, and he was gathered to his people.
01Gn 25:18 His descendants settled in the area from Havilah to Shur, near the border of Egypt, as you go toward Asshur. And they lived in hostility toward all their brothers.
01Gn 25:19 This is the account of Abraham's son Isaac. Abraham became the father of Isaac,
01Gn 25:20 and Isaac was forty years old when he married Rebekah daughter of Bethuel the Aramean from Paddan Aram and sister of Laban the Aramean.
01Gn 25:21 Isaac prayed to the LORD on behalf of his wife, because she was barren. The LORD answered his prayer, and his wife Rebekah became pregnant.
01Gn 25:22 The babies jostled each other within her, and she said, "Why is this happening to me?" So she went to inquire of the LORD.
01Gn 25:23 The LORD said to her, "Two nations are in your womb, and two peoples from within you will be separated; one people will be stronger than the other, and the older will serve the younger."
01Gn 25:24 When the time came for her to give birth, there were twin boys in her womb.
01Gn 25:25 The first to come out was red, and his whole body was like a hairy garment; so they named him Esau.
01Gn 25:26 After this, his brother came out, with his hand grasping Esau's heel; so he was named Jacob. Isaac was sixty years old when Rebekah gave birth to them.
01Gn 25:27 The boys grew up, and Esau became a skillful hunter, a man of the open country, while Jacob was a quiet man, staying among the tents.
01Gn 25:28 Isaac, who had a taste for wild game, loved Esau, but Rebekah loved Jacob.
01Gn 25:29 Once when Jacob was cooking some stew, Esau came in from the open country, famished.
01Gn 25:30 He said to Jacob, "Quick, let me have some of that red stew! I'm famished!" (That is why he was also called Edom.)
01Gn 25:31 Jacob replied, "First sell me your birthright."
01Gn 25:32 "Look, I am about to die," Esau said. "What good is the birthright to me?"
01Gn 25:33 But Jacob said, "Swear to me first." So he swore an oath to him, selling his birthright to Jacob.
01Gn 25:34 Then Jacob gave Esau some bread and some lentil stew. He ate and drank, and then got up and left. So Esau despised his birthright.
01Gn 26:1 Now there was a famine in the land--besides the earlier famine of Abraham's time--and Isaac went to Abimelech king of the Philistines in Gerar.
01Gn 26:2 The LORD appeared to Isaac and said, "Do not go down to Egypt; live in the land where I tell you to live.
01Gn 26:3 Stay in this land for a while, and I will be with you and will bless you. For to you and your descendants I will give all these lands and will confirm the oath I swore to your father Abraham.
01Gn 26:4 I will make your descendants as numerous as the stars in the sky and will give them all these lands, and through your offspring all nations on earth will be blessed,
01Gn 26:5 because Abraham obeyed me and kept my requirements, my commands, my decrees and my laws."
01Gn 26:6 So Isaac stayed in Gerar.
01Gn 26:7 When the men of that place asked him about his wife, he said, "She is my sister," because he was afraid to say, "She is my wife." He thought, "The men of this place might kill me on account of Rebekah, because she is beautiful."
01Gn 26:8 When Isaac had been there a long time, Abimelech king of the Philistines looked down from a window and saw Isaac caressing his wife Rebekah.
01Gn 26:9 So Abimelech summoned Isaac and said, "She is really your wife! Why did you say, 'She is my sister'?" Isaac answered him, "Because I thought I might lose my life on account of her."
01Gn 26:10 Then Abimelech said, "What is this you have done to us? One of the men might well have slept with your wife, and you would have brought guilt upon us."
01Gn 26:11 So Abimelech gave orders to all the people£º "Anyone who molests this man or his wife shall surely be put to death."
01Gn 26:12 Isaac planted crops in that land and the same year reaped a hundredfold, because the LORD blessed him.
01Gn 26:13 The man became rich, and his wealth continued to grow until he became very wealthy.
01Gn 26:14 He had so many flocks and herds and servants that the Philistines envied him.
01Gn 26:15 So all the wells that his father's servants had dug in the time of his father Abraham, the Philistines stopped up, filling them with earth.
01Gn 26:16 Then Abimelech said to Isaac, "Move away from us; you have become too powerful for us."
01Gn 26:17 So Isaac moved away from there and encamped in the Valley of Gerar and settled there.
01Gn 26:18 Isaac reopened the wells that had been dug in the time of his father Abraham, which the Philistines had stopped up after Abraham died, and he gave them the same names his father had given them.
01Gn 26:19 Isaac's servants dug in the valley and discovered a well of fresh water there.
01Gn 26:20 But the herdsmen of Gerar quarreled with Isaac's herdsmen and said, "The water is ours!" So he named the well Esek, because they disputed with him.
01Gn 26:21 Then they dug another well, but they quarreled over that one also; so he named it Sitnah.
01Gn 26:22 He moved on from there and dug another well, and no one quarreled over it. He named it Rehoboth, saying, "Now the LORD has given us room and we will flourish in the land."
01Gn 26:23 From there he went up to Beersheba.
01Gn 26:24 That night the LORD appeared to him and said, "I am the God of your father Abraham. Do not be afraid, for I am with you; I will bless you and will increase the number of your descendants for the sake of my servant Abraham."
01Gn 26:25 Isaac built an altar there and called on the name of the LORD. There he pitched his tent, and there his servants dug a well.
01Gn 26:26 Meanwhile, Abimelech had come to him from Gerar, with Ahuzzath his personal adviser and Phicol the commander of his forces.
01Gn 26:27 Isaac asked them, "Why have you come to me, since you were hostile to me and sent me away?"
01Gn 26:28 They answered, "We saw clearly that the LORD was with you; so we said, 'There ought to be a sworn agreement between us'--between us and you. Let us make a treaty with you
01Gn 26:29 that you will do us no harm, just as we did not molest you but always treated you well and sent you away in peace. And now you are blessed by the LORD."
01Gn 26:30 Isaac then made a feast for them, and they ate and drank.
01Gn 26:31 Early the next morning the men swore an oath to each other. Then Isaac sent them on their way, and they left him in peace.
01Gn 26:32 That day Isaac's servants came and told him about the well they had dug. They said, "We've found water!"
01Gn 26:33 He called it Shibah, and to this day the name of the town has been Beersheba.
01Gn 26:34 When Esau was forty years old, he married Judith daughter of Beeri the Hittite, and also Basemath daughter of Elon the Hittite.
01Gn 26:35 They were a source of grief to Isaac and Rebekah.
01Gn 27:1 When Isaac was old and his eyes were so weak that he could no longer see, he called for Esau his older son and said to him, "My son." "Here I am," he answered.
01Gn 27:2 Isaac said, "I am now an old man and don't know the day of my death.
01Gn 27:3 Now then, get your weapons--your quiver and bow--and go out to the open country to hunt some wild game for me.
01Gn 27:4 Prepare me the kind of tasty food I like and bring it to me to eat, so that I may give you my blessing before I die."
01Gn 27:5 Now Rebekah was listening as Isaac spoke to his son Esau. When Esau left for the open country to hunt game and bring it back,
01Gn 27:6 Rebekah said to her son Jacob, "Look, I overheard your father say to your brother Esau,
01Gn 27:7 'Bring me some game and prepare me some tasty food to eat, so that I may give you my blessing in the presence of the LORD before I die.'
01Gn 27:8 Now, my son, listen carefully and do what I tell you£º
01Gn 27:9 Go out to the flock and bring me two choice young goats, so I can prepare some tasty food for your father, just the way he likes it.
01Gn 27:10 Then take it to your father to eat, so that he may give you his blessing before he dies."
01Gn 27:11 Jacob said to Rebekah his mother, "But my brother Esau is a hairy man, and I'm a man with smooth skin.
01Gn 27:12 What if my father touches me? I would appear to be tricking him and would bring down a curse on myself rather than a blessing."
01Gn 27:13 His mother said to him, "My son, let the curse fall on me. Just do what I say; go and get them for me."
01Gn 27:14 So he went and got them and brought them to his mother, and she prepared some tasty food, just the way his father liked it.
01Gn 27:15 Then Rebekah took the best clothes of Esau her older son, which she had in the house, and put them on her younger son Jacob.
01Gn 27:16 She also covered his hands and the smooth part of his neck with the goatskins.
01Gn 27:17 Then she handed to her son Jacob the tasty food and the bread she had made.
01Gn 27:18 He went to his father and said, "My father." "Yes, my son," he answered. "Who is it?"
01Gn 27:19 Jacob said to his father, "I am Esau your firstborn. I have done as you told me. Please sit up and eat some of my game so that you may give me your blessing."
01Gn 27:20 Isaac asked his son, "How did you find it so quickly, my son?" "The LORD your God gave me success," he replied.
01Gn 27:21 Then Isaac said to Jacob, "Come near so I can touch you, my son, to know whether you really are my son Esau or not."
01Gn 27:22 Jacob went close to his father Isaac, who touched him and said, "The voice is the voice of Jacob, but the hands are the hands of Esau."
01Gn 27:23 He did not recognize him, for his hands were hairy like those of his brother Esau; so he blessed him.
01Gn 27:24 "Are you really my son Esau?" he asked. "I am," he replied.
01Gn 27:25 Then he said, "My son, bring me some of your game to eat, so that I may give you my blessing." Jacob brought it to him and he ate; and he brought some wine and he drank.
01Gn 27:26 Then his father Isaac said to him, "Come here, my son, and kiss me."
01Gn 27:27 So he went to him and kissed him. When Isaac caught the smell of his clothes, he blessed him and said, "Ah, the smell of my son is like the smell of a field that the LORD has blessed.
01Gn 27:28 May God give you of heaven's dew and of earth's richness--an abundance of grain and new wine.
01Gn 27:29 May nations serve you and peoples bow down to you. Be lord over your brothers, and may the sons of your mother bow down to you. May those who curse you be cursed and those who bless you be blessed."
01Gn 27:30 After Isaac finished blessing him and Jacob had scarcely left his father's presence, his brother Esau came in from hunting.
01Gn 27:31 He too prepared some tasty food and brought it to his father. Then he said to him, "My father, sit up and eat some of my game, so that you may give me your blessing."
01Gn 27:32 His father Isaac asked him, "Who are you?" "I am your son," he answered, "your firstborn, Esau."
01Gn 27:33 Isaac trembled violently and said, "Who was it, then, that hunted game and brought it to me? I ate it just before you came and I blessed him--and indeed he will be blessed!"
01Gn 27:34 When Esau heard his father's words, he burst out with a loud and bitter cry and said to his father, "Bless me--me too, my father!"
01Gn 27:35 But he said, "Your brother came deceitfully and took your blessing."
01Gn 27:36 Esau said, "Isn't he rightly named Jacob? He has deceived me these two times£º He took my birthright, and now he's taken my blessing!" Then he asked, "Haven't you reserved any blessing for me?"
01Gn 27:37 Isaac answered Esau, "I have made him lord over you and have made all his relatives his servants, and I have sustained him with grain and new wine. So what can I possibly do for you, my son?"
01Gn 27:38 Esau said to his father, "Do you have only one blessing, my father? Bless me too, my father!" Then Esau wept aloud.
01Gn 27:39 His father Isaac answered him, "Your dwelling will be away from the earth's richness, away from the dew of heaven above.
01Gn 27:40 You will live by the sword and you will serve your brother. But when you grow restless, you will throw his yoke from off your neck."
01Gn 27:41 Esau held a grudge against Jacob because of the blessing his father had given him. He said to himself, "The days of mourning for my father are near; then I will kill my brother Jacob."
01Gn 27:42 When Rebekah was told what her older son Esau had said, she sent for her younger son Jacob and said to him, "Your brother Esau is consoling himself with the thought of killing you.
01Gn 27:43 Now then, my son, do what I say£º Flee at once to my brother Laban in Haran.
01Gn 27:44 Stay with him for a while until your brother's fury subsides.
01Gn 27:45 When your brother is no longer angry with you and forgets what you did to him, I'll send word for you to come back from there. Why should I lose both of you in one day?"
01Gn 27:46 Then Rebekah said to Isaac, "I'm disgusted with living because of these Hittite women. If Jacob takes a wife from among the women of this land, from Hittite women like these, my life will not be worth living."
01Gn 28:1 So Isaac called for Jacob and blessed him and commanded him£º "Do not marry a Canaanite woman.
01Gn 28:2 Go at once to Paddan Aram, to the house of your mother's father Bethuel. Take a wife for yourself there, from among the daughters of Laban, your mother's brother.
01Gn 28:3 May God Almighty bless you and make you fruitful and increase your numbers until you become a community of peoples.
01Gn 28:4 May he give you and your descendants the blessing given to Abraham, so that you may take possession of the land where you now live as an alien, the land God gave to Abraham."
01Gn 28:5 Then Isaac sent Jacob on his way, and he went to Paddan Aram, to Laban son of Bethuel the Aramean, the brother of Rebekah, who was the mother of Jacob and Esau.
01Gn 28:6 Now Esau learned that Isaac had blessed Jacob and had sent him to Paddan Aram to take a wife from there, and that when he blessed him he commanded him, "Do not marry a Canaanite woman,"
01Gn 28:7 and that Jacob had obeyed his father and mother and had gone to Paddan Aram.
01Gn 28:8 Esau then realized how displeasing the Canaanite women were to his father Isaac;
01Gn 28:9 so he went to Ishmael and married Mahalath, the sister of Nebaioth and daughter of Ishmael son of Abraham, in addition to the wives he already had.
01Gn 28:10 Jacob left Beersheba and set out for Haran.
01Gn 28:11 When he reached a certain place, he stopped for the night because the sun had set. Taking one of the stones there, he put it under his head and lay down to sleep.
01Gn 28:12 He had a dream in which he saw a stairway resting on the earth, with its top reaching to heaven, and the angels of God were ascending and descending on it.
01Gn 28:13 There above it stood the LORD, and he said£º "I am the LORD, the God of your father Abraham and the God of Isaac. I will give you and your descendants the land on which you are lying.
01Gn 28:14 Your descendants will be like the dust of the earth, and you will spread out to the west and to the east, to the north and to the south. All peoples on earth will be blessed through you and your offspring.
01Gn 28:15 I am with you and will watch over you wherever you go, and I will bring you back to this land. I will not leave you until I have done what I have promised you."
01Gn 28:16 When Jacob awoke from his sleep, he thought, "Surely the LORD is in this place, and I was not aware of it."
01Gn 28:17 He was afraid and said, "How awesome is this place! This is none other than the house of God; this is the gate of heaven."
01Gn 28:18 Early the next morning Jacob took the stone he had placed under his head and set it up as a pillar and poured oil on top of it.
01Gn 28:19 He called that place Bethel, though the city used to be called Luz.
01Gn 28:20 Then Jacob made a vow, saying, "If God will be with me and will watch over me on this journey I am taking and will give me food to eat and clothes to wear
01Gn 28:21 so that I return safely to my father's house, then the LORD will be my God
01Gn 28:22 and this stone that I have set up as a pillar will be God's house, and of all that you give me I will give you a tenth."
01Gn 29:1 Then Jacob continued on his journey and came to the land of the eastern peoples.
01Gn 29:2 There he saw a well in the field, with three flocks of sheep lying near it because the flocks were watered from that well. The stone over the mouth of the well was large.
01Gn 29:3 When all the flocks were gathered there, the shepherds would roll the stone away from the well's mouth and water the sheep. Then they would return the stone to its place over the mouth of the well.
01Gn 29:4 Jacob asked the shepherds, "My brothers, where are you from?" "We're from Haran," they replied.
01Gn 29:5 He said to them, "Do you know Laban, Nahor's grandson?" "Yes, we know him," they answered.
01Gn 29:6 Then Jacob asked them, "Is he well?" "Yes, he is," they said, "and here comes his daughter Rachel with the sheep."
01Gn 29:7 "Look," he said, "the sun is still high; it is not time for the flocks to be gathered. Water the sheep and take them back to pasture."
01Gn 29:8 "We can't," they replied, "until all the flocks are gathered and the stone has been rolled away from the mouth of the well. Then we will water the sheep."
01Gn 29:9 While he was still talking with them, Rachel came with her father's sheep, for she was a shepherdess.
01Gn 29:10 When Jacob saw Rachel daughter of Laban, his mother's brother, and Laban's sheep, he went over and rolled the stone away from the mouth of the well and watered his uncle's sheep.
01Gn 29:11 Then Jacob kissed Rachel and began to weep aloud.
01Gn 29:12 He had told Rachel that he was a relative of her father and a son of Rebekah. So she ran and told her father.
01Gn 29:13 As soon as Laban heard the news about Jacob, his sister's son, he hurried to meet him. He embraced him and kissed him and brought him to his home, and there Jacob told him all these things.
01Gn 29:14 Then Laban said to him, "You are my own flesh and blood." After Jacob had stayed with him for a whole month,
01Gn 29:15 Laban said to him, "Just because you are a relative of mine, should you work for me for nothing? Tell me what your wages should be."
01Gn 29:16 Now Laban had two daughters; the name of the older was Leah, and the name of the younger was Rachel.
01Gn 29:17 Leah had weak eyes, but Rachel was lovely in form, and beautiful.
01Gn 29:18 Jacob was in love with Rachel and said, "I'll work for you seven years in return for your younger daughter Rachel."
01Gn 29:19 Laban said, "It's better that I give her to you than to some other man. Stay here with me."
01Gn 29:20 So Jacob served seven years to get Rachel, but they seemed like only a few days to him because of his love for her.
01Gn 29:21 Then Jacob said to Laban, "Give me my wife. My time is completed, and I want to lie with her."
01Gn 29:22 So Laban brought together all the people of the place and gave a feast.
01Gn 29:23 But when evening came, he took his daughter Leah and gave her to Jacob, and Jacob lay with her.
01Gn 29:24 And Laban gave his servant girl Zilpah to his daughter as her maidservant.
01Gn 29:25 When morning came, there was Leah! So Jacob said to Laban, "What is this you have done to me? I served you for Rachel, didn't I? Why have you deceived me?"
01Gn 29:26 Laban replied, "It is not our custom here to give the younger daughter in marriage before the older one.
01Gn 29:27 Finish this daughter's bridal week; then we will give you the younger one also, in return for another seven years of work."
01Gn 29:28 And Jacob did so. He finished the week with Leah, and then Laban gave him his daughter Rachel to be his wife.
01Gn 29:29 Laban gave his servant girl Bilhah to his daughter Rachel as her maidservant.
01Gn 29:30 Jacob lay with Rachel also, and he loved Rachel more than Leah. And he worked for Laban another seven years.
01Gn 29:31 When the LORD saw that Leah was not loved, he opened her womb, but Rachel was barren.
01Gn 29:32 Leah became pregnant and gave birth to a son. She named him Reuben, for she said, "It is because the LORD has seen my misery. Surely my husband will love me now."
01Gn 29:33 She conceived again, and when she gave birth to a son she said, "Because the LORD heard that I am not loved, he gave me this one too." So she named him Simeon.
01Gn 29:34 Again she conceived, and when she gave birth to a son she said, "Now at last my husband will become attached to me, because I have borne him three sons." So he was named Levi.
01Gn 29:35 She conceived again, and when she gave birth to a son she said, "This time I will praise the LORD." So she named him Judah. Then she stopped having children.
01Gn 30:1 When Rachel saw that she was not bearing Jacob any children, she became jealous of her sister. So she said to Jacob, "Give me children, or I'll die!"
01Gn 30:2 Jacob became angry with her and said, "Am I in the place of God, who has kept you from having children?"
01Gn 30:3 Then she said, "Here is Bilhah, my maidservant. Sleep with her so that she can bear children for me and that through her I too can build a family."
01Gn 30:4 So she gave him her servant Bilhah as a wife. Jacob slept with her,
01Gn 30:5 and she became pregnant and bore him a son.
01Gn 30:6 Then Rachel said, "God has vindicated me; he has listened to my plea and given me a son." Because of this she named him Dan.
01Gn 30:7 Rachel's servant Bilhah conceived again and bore Jacob a second son.
01Gn 30:8 Then Rachel said, "I have had a great struggle with my sister, and I have won." So she named him Naphtali.
01Gn 30:9 When Leah saw that she had stopped having children, she took her maidservant Zilpah and gave her to Jacob as a wife.
01Gn 30:10 Leah's servant Zilpah bore Jacob a son.
01Gn 30:11 Then Leah said, "What good fortune!" So she named him Gad.
01Gn 30:12 Leah's servant Zilpah bore Jacob a second son.
01Gn 30:13 Then Leah said, "How happy I am! The women will call me happy." So she named him Asher.
01Gn 30:14 During wheat harvest, Reuben went out into the fields and found some mandrake plants, which he brought to his mother Leah. Rachel said to Leah, "Please give me some of your son's mandrakes."
01Gn 30:15 But she said to her, "Wasn't it enough that you took away my husband? Will you take my son's mandrakes too?" "Very well," Rachel said, "he can sleep with you tonight in return for your son's mandrakes."
01Gn 30:16 So when Jacob came in from the fields that evening, Leah went out to meet him. "You must sleep with me," she said. "I have hired you with my son's mandrakes." So he slept with her that night.
01Gn 30:17 God listened to Leah, and she became pregnant and bore Jacob a fifth son.
01Gn 30:18 Then Leah said, "God has rewarded me for giving my maidservant to my husband." So she named him Issachar.
01Gn 30:19 Leah conceived again and bore Jacob a sixth son.
01Gn 30:20 Then Leah said, "God has presented me with a precious gift. This time my husband will treat me with honor, because I have borne him six sons." So she named him Zebulun.
01Gn 30:21 Some time later she gave birth to a daughter and named her Dinah.
01Gn 30:22 Then God remembered Rachel; he listened to her and opened her womb.
01Gn 30:23 She became pregnant and gave birth to a son and said, "God has taken away my disgrace."
01Gn 30:24 She named him Joseph, and said, "May the LORD add to me another son."
01Gn 30:25 After Rachel gave birth to Joseph, Jacob said to Laban, "Send me on my way so I can go back to my own homeland.
01Gn 30:26 Give me my wives and children, for whom I have served you, and I will be on my way. You know how much work I've done for you."
01Gn 30:27 But Laban said to him, "If I have found favor in your eyes, please stay. I have learned by divination that the LORD has blessed me because of you."
01Gn 30:28 He added, "Name your wages, and I will pay them."
01Gn 30:29 Jacob said to him, "You know how I have worked for you and how your livestock has fared under my care.
01Gn 30:30 The little you had before I came has increased greatly, and the LORD has blessed you wherever I have been. But now, when may I do something for my own household?"
01Gn 30:31 "What shall I give you?" he asked. "Don't give me anything," Jacob replied. "But if you will do this one thing for me, I will go on tending your flocks and watching over them£º
01Gn 30:32 Let me go through all your flocks today and remove from them every speckled or spotted sheep, every dark-colored lamb and every spotted or speckled goat. They will be my wages.
01Gn 30:33 And my honesty will testify for me in the future, whenever you check on the wages you have paid me. Any goat in my possession that is not speckled or spotted, or any lamb that is not dark-colored, will be considered stolen."
01Gn 30:34 "Agreed," said Laban. "Let it be as you have said."
01Gn 30:35 That same day he removed all the male goats that were streaked or spotted, and all the speckled or spotted female goats (all that had white on them) and all the dark-colored lambs, and he placed them in the care of his sons.
01Gn 30:36 Then he put a three-day journey between himself and Jacob, while Jacob continued to tend the rest of Laban's flocks.
01Gn 30:37 Jacob, however, took fresh-cut branches from poplar, almond and plane trees and made white stripes on them by peeling the bark and exposing the white inner wood of the branches.
01Gn 30:38 Then he placed the peeled branches in all the watering troughs, so that they would be directly in front of the flocks when they came to drink. When the flocks were in heat and came to drink,
01Gn 30:39 they mated in front of the branches. And they bore young that were streaked or speckled or spotted.
01Gn 30:40 Jacob set apart the young of the flock by themselves, but made the rest face the streaked and dark-colored animals that belonged to Laban. Thus he made separate flocks for himself and did not put them with Laban's animals.
01Gn 30:41 Whenever the stronger females were in heat, Jacob would place the branches in the troughs in front of the animals so they would mate near the branches,
01Gn 30:42 but if the animals were weak, he would not place them there. So the weak animals went to Laban and the strong ones to Jacob.
01Gn 30:43 In this way the man grew exceedingly prosperous and came to own large flocks, and maidservants and menservants, and camels and donkeys.
01Gn 31:1 Jacob heard that Laban's sons were saying, "Jacob has taken everything our father owned and has gained all this wealth from what belonged to our father."
01Gn 31:2 And Jacob noticed that Laban's attitude toward him was not what it had been.
01Gn 31:3 Then the LORD said to Jacob, "Go back to the land of your fathers and to your relatives, and I will be with you."
01Gn 31:4 So Jacob sent word to Rachel and Leah to come out to the fields where his flocks were.
01Gn 31:5 He said to them, "I see that your father's attitude toward me is not what it was before, but the God of my father has been with me.
01Gn 31:6 You know that I've worked for your father with all my strength,
01Gn 31:7 yet your father has cheated me by changing my wages ten times. However, God has not allowed him to harm me.
01Gn 31:8 If he said, 'The speckled ones will be your wages,' then all the flocks gave birth to speckled young; and if he said, 'The streaked ones will be your wages,' then all the flocks bore streaked young.
01Gn 31:9 So God has taken away your father's livestock and has given them to me.
01Gn 31:10 "In breeding season I once had a dream in which I looked up and saw that the male goats mating with the flock were streaked, speckled or spotted.
01Gn 31:11 The angel of God said to me in the dream, 'Jacob.' I answered, 'Here I am.'
01Gn 31:12 And he said, 'Look up and see that all the male goats mating with the flock are streaked, speckled or spotted, for I have seen all that Laban has been doing to you.
01Gn 31:13 I am the God of Bethel, where you anointed a pillar and where you made a vow to me. Now leave this land at once and go back to your native land.'"
01Gn 31:14 Then Rachel and Leah replied, "Do we still have any share in the inheritance of our father's estate?
01Gn 31:15 Does he not regard us as foreigners? Not only has he sold us, but he has used up what was paid for us.
01Gn 31:16 Surely all the wealth that God took away from our father belongs to us and our children. So do whatever God has told you."
01Gn 31:17 Then Jacob put his children and his wives on camels,
01Gn 31:18 and he drove all his livestock ahead of him, along with all the goods he had accumulated in Paddan Aram, to go to his father Isaac in the land of Canaan.
01Gn 31:19 When Laban had gone to shear his sheep, Rachel stole her father's household gods.
01Gn 31:20 Moreover, Jacob deceived Laban the Aramean by not telling him he was running away.
01Gn 31:21 So he fled with all he had, and crossing the River, he headed for the hill country of Gilead.
01Gn 31:22 On the third day Laban was told that Jacob had fled.
01Gn 31:23 Taking his relatives with him, he pursued Jacob for seven days and caught up with him in the hill country of Gilead.
01Gn 31:24 Then God came to Laban the Aramean in a dream at night and said to him, "Be careful not to say anything to Jacob, either good or bad."
01Gn 31:25 Jacob had pitched his tent in the hill country of Gilead when Laban overtook him, and Laban and his relatives camped there too.
01Gn 31:26 Then Laban said to Jacob, "What have you done? You've deceived me, and you've carried off my daughters like captives in war.
01Gn 31:27 Why did you run off secretly and deceive me? Why didn't you tell me, so I could send you away with joy and singing to the music of tambourines and harps?
01Gn 31:28 You didn't even let me kiss my grandchildren and my daughters good-by. You have done a foolish thing.
01Gn 31:29 I have the power to harm you; but last night the God of your father said to me, 'Be careful not to say anything to Jacob, either good or bad.'
01Gn 31:30 Now you have gone off because you longed to return to your father's house. But why did you steal my gods?"
01Gn 31:31 Jacob answered Laban, "I was afraid, because I thought you would take your daughters away from me by force.
01Gn 31:32 But if you find anyone who has your gods, he shall not live. In the presence of our relatives, see for yourself whether there is anything of yours here with me; and if so, take it." Now Jacob did not know that Rachel had stolen the gods.
01Gn 31:33 So Laban went into Jacob's tent and into Leah's tent and into the tent of the two maidservants, but he found nothing. After he came out of Leah's tent, he entered Rachel's tent.
01Gn 31:34 Now Rachel had taken the household gods and put them inside her camel's saddle and was sitting on them. Laban searched through everything in the tent but found nothing.
01Gn 31:35 Rachel said to her father, "Don't be angry, my lord, that I cannot stand up in your presence; I'm having my period." So he searched but could not find the household gods.
01Gn 31:36 Jacob was angry and took Laban to task. "What is my crime?" he asked Laban. "What sin have I committed that you hunt me down?
01Gn 31:37 Now that you have searched through all my goods, what have you found that belongs to your household? Put it here in front of your relatives and mine, and let them judge between the two of us.
01Gn 31:38 "I have been with you for twenty years now. Your sheep and goats have not miscarried, nor have I eaten rams from your flocks.
01Gn 31:39 I did not bring you animals torn by wild beasts; I bore the loss myself. And you demanded payment from me for whatever was stolen by day or night.
01Gn 31:40 This was my situation£º The heat consumed me in the daytime and the cold at night, and sleep fled from my eyes.
01Gn 31:41 It was like this for the twenty years I was in your household. I worked for you fourteen years for your two daughters and six years for your flocks, and you changed my wages ten times.
01Gn 31:42 If the God of my father, the God of Abraham and the Fear of Isaac, had not been with me, you would surely have sent me away empty-handed. But God has seen my hardship and the toil of my hands, and last night he rebuked you."
01Gn 31:43 Laban answered Jacob, "The women are my daughters, the children are my children, and the flocks are my flocks. All you see is mine. Yet what can I do today about these daughters of mine, or about the children they have borne?
01Gn 31:44 Come now, let's make a covenant, you and I, and let it serve as a witness between us."
01Gn 31:45 So Jacob took a stone and set it up as a pillar.
01Gn 31:46 He said to his relatives, "Gather some stones." So they took stones and piled them in a heap, and they ate there by the heap.
01Gn 31:47 Laban called it Jegar Sahadutha, and Jacob called it Galeed.
01Gn 31:48 Laban said, "This heap is a witness between you and me today." That is why it was called Galeed.
01Gn 31:49 It was also called Mizpah, because he said, "May the LORD keep watch between you and me when we are away from each other.
01Gn 31:50 If you mistreat my daughters or if you take any wives besides my daughters, even though no one is with us, remember that God is a witness between you and me."
01Gn 31:51 Laban also said to Jacob, "Here is this heap, and here is this pillar I have set up between you and me.
01Gn 31:52 This heap is a witness, and this pillar is a witness, that I will not go past this heap to your side to harm you and that you will not go past this heap and pillar to my side to harm me.
01Gn 31:53 May the God of Abraham and the God of Nahor, the God of their father, judge between us." So Jacob took an oath in the name of the Fear of his father Isaac.
01Gn 31:54 He offered a sacrifice there in the hill country and invited his relatives to a meal. After they had eaten, they spent the night there.
01Gn 31:55 Early the next morning Laban kissed his grandchildren and his daughters and blessed them. Then he left and returned home.
01Gn 32:1 Jacob also went on his way, and the angels of God met him.
01Gn 32:2 When Jacob saw them, he said, "This is the camp of God!" So he named that place Mahanaim.
01Gn 32:3 Jacob sent messengers ahead of him to his brother Esau in the land of Seir, the country of Edom.
01Gn 32:4 He instructed them£º "This is what you are to say to my master Esau£º 'Your servant Jacob says, I have been staying with Laban and have remained there till now.
01Gn 32:5 I have cattle and donkeys, sheep and goats, menservants and maidservants. Now I am sending this message to my lord, that I may find favor in your eyes.'"
01Gn 32:6 When the messengers returned to Jacob, they said, "We went to your brother Esau, and now he is coming to meet you, and four hundred men are with him."
01Gn 32:7 In great fear and distress Jacob divided the people who were with him into two groups, and the flocks and herds and camels as well.
01Gn 32:8 He thought, "If Esau comes and attacks one group, the group that is left may escape."
01Gn 32:9 Then Jacob prayed, "O God of my father Abraham, God of my father Isaac, O LORD, who said to me, 'Go back to your country and your relatives, and I will make you prosper,'
01Gn 32:10 I am unworthy of all the kindness and faithfulness you have shown your servant. I had only my staff when I crossed this Jordan, but now I have become two groups.
01Gn 32:11 Save me, I pray, from the hand of my brother Esau, for I am afraid he will come and attack me, and also the mothers with their children.
01Gn 32:12 But you have said, 'I will surely make you prosper and will make your descendants like the sand of the sea, which cannot be counted.'"
01Gn 32:13 He spent the night there, and from what he had with him he selected a gift for his brother Esau£º
01Gn 32:14 two hundred female goats and twenty male goats, two hundred ewes and twenty rams,
01Gn 32:15 thirty female camels with their young, forty cows and ten bulls, and twenty female donkeys and ten male donkeys.
01Gn 32:16 He put them in the care of his servants, each herd by itself, and said to his servants, "Go ahead of me, and keep some space between the herds."
01Gn 32:17 He instructed the one in the lead£º "When my brother Esau meets you and asks, 'To whom do you belong, and where are you going, and who owns all these animals in front of you?'
01Gn 32:18 then you are to say, 'They belong to your servant Jacob. They are a gift sent to my lord Esau, and he is coming behind us.'"
01Gn 32:19 He also instructed the second, the third and all the others who followed the herds£º "You are to say the same thing to Esau when you meet him.
01Gn 32:20 And be sure to say, 'Your servant Jacob is coming behind us.'" For he thought, "I will pacify him with these gifts I am sending on ahead; later, when I see him, perhaps he will receive me."
01Gn 32:21 So Jacob's gifts went on ahead of him, but he himself spent the night in the camp.
01Gn 32:22 That night Jacob got up and took his two wives, his two maidservants and his eleven sons and crossed the ford of the Jabbok.
01Gn 32:23 After he had sent them across the stream, he sent over all his possessions.
01Gn 32:24 So Jacob was left alone, and a man wrestled with him till daybreak.
01Gn 32:25 When the man saw that he could not overpower him, he touched the socket of Jacob's hip so that his hip was wrenched as he wrestled with the man.
01Gn 32:26 Then the man said, "Let me go, for it is daybreak." But Jacob replied, "I will not let you go unless you bless me."
01Gn 32:27 The man asked him, "What is your name?" "Jacob," he answered.
01Gn 32:28 Then the man said, "Your name will no longer be Jacob, but Israel, because you have struggled with God and with men and have overcome."
01Gn 32:29 Jacob said, "Please tell me your name." But he replied, "Why do you ask my name?" Then he blessed him there.
01Gn 32:30 So Jacob called the place Peniel, saying, "It is because I saw God face to face, and yet my life was spared."
01Gn 32:31 The sun rose above him as he passed Peniel, and he was limping because of his hip.
01Gn 32:32 Therefore to this day the Israelites do not eat the tendon attached to the socket of the hip, because the socket of Jacob's hip was touched near the tendon.
01Gn 33:1 Jacob looked up and there was Esau, coming with his four hundred men; so he divided the children among Leah, Rachel and the two maidservants.
01Gn 33:2 He put the maidservants and their children in front, Leah and her children next, and Rachel and Joseph in the rear.
01Gn 33:3 He himself went on ahead and bowed down to the ground seven times as he approached his brother.
01Gn 33:4 But Esau ran to meet Jacob and embraced him; he threw his arms around his neck and kissed him. And they wept.
01Gn 33:5 Then Esau looked up and saw the women and children. "Who are these with you?" he asked. Jacob answered, "They are the children God has graciously given your servant."
01Gn 33:6 Then the maidservants and their children approached and bowed down.
01Gn 33:7 Next, Leah and her children came and bowed down. Last of all came Joseph and Rachel, and they too bowed down.
01Gn 33:8 Esau asked, "What do you mean by all these droves I met?" "To find favor in your eyes, my lord," he said.
01Gn 33:9 But Esau said, "I already have plenty, my brother. Keep what you have for yourself."
01Gn 33:10 "No, please!" said Jacob. "If I have found favor in your eyes, accept this gift from me. For to see your face is like seeing the face of God, now that you have received me favorably.
01Gn 33:11 Please accept the present that was brought to you, for God has been gracious to me and I have all I need." And because Jacob insisted, Esau accepted it.
01Gn 33:12 Then Esau said, "Let us be on our way; I'll accompany you."
01Gn 33:13 But Jacob said to him, "My lord knows that the children are tender and that I must care for the ewes and cows that are nursing their young. If they are driven hard just one day, all the animals will die.
01Gn 33:14 So let my lord go on ahead of his servant, while I move along slowly at the pace of the droves before me and that of the children, until I come to my lord in Seir."
01Gn 33:15 Esau said, "Then let me leave some of my men with you." "But why do that?" Jacob asked. "Just let me find favor in the eyes of my lord."
01Gn 33:16 So that day Esau started on his way back to Seir.
01Gn 33:17 Jacob, however, went to Succoth, where he built a place for himself and made shelters for his livestock. That is why the place is called Succoth.
01Gn 33:18 After Jacob came from Paddan Aram, he arrived safely at the city of Shechem in Canaan and camped within sight of the city.
01Gn 33:19 For a hundred pieces of silver, he bought from the sons of Hamor, the father of Shechem, the plot of ground where he pitched his tent.
01Gn 33:20 There he set up an altar and called it El Elohe Israel.
01Gn 34:1 Now Dinah, the daughter Leah had borne to Jacob, went out to visit the women of the land.
01Gn 34:2 When Shechem son of Hamor the Hivite, the ruler of that area, saw her, he took her and violated her.
01Gn 34:3 His heart was drawn to Dinah daughter of Jacob, and he loved the girl and spoke tenderly to her.
01Gn 34:4 And Shechem said to his father Hamor, "Get me this girl as my wife."
01Gn 34:5 When Jacob heard that his daughter Dinah had been defiled, his sons were in the fields with his livestock; so he kept quiet about it until they came home.
01Gn 34:6 Then Shechem's father Hamor went out to talk with Jacob.
01Gn 34:7 Now Jacob's sons had come in from the fields as soon as they heard what had happened. They were filled with grief and fury, because Shechem had done a disgraceful thing in Israel by lying with Jacob's daughter--a thing that should not be done.
01Gn 34:8 But Hamor said to them, "My son Shechem has his heart set on your daughter. Please give her to him as his wife.
01Gn 34:9 Intermarry with us; give us your daughters and take our daughters for yourselves.
01Gn 34:10 You can settle among us; the land is open to you. Live in it, trade in it, and acquire property in it."
01Gn 34:11 Then Shechem said to Dinah's father and brothers, "Let me find favor in your eyes, and I will give you whatever you ask.
01Gn 34:12 Make the price for the bride and the gift I am to bring as great as you like, and I'll pay whatever you ask me. Only give me the girl as my wife."
01Gn 34:13 Because their sister Dinah had been defiled, Jacob's sons replied deceitfully as they spoke to Shechem and his father Hamor.
01Gn 34:14 They said to them, "We can't do such a thing; we can't give our sister to a man who is not circumcised. That would be a disgrace to us.
01Gn 34:15 We will give our consent to you on one condition only£º that you become like us by circumcising all your males.
01Gn 34:16 Then we will give you our daughters and take your daughters for ourselves. We'll settle among you and become one people with you.
01Gn 34:17 But if you will not agree to be circumcised, we'll take our sister and go."
01Gn 34:18 Their proposal seemed good to Hamor and his son Shechem.
01Gn 34:19 The young man, who was the most honored of all his father's household, lost no time in doing what they said, because he was delighted with Jacob's daughter.
01Gn 34:20 So Hamor and his son Shechem went to the gate of their city to speak to their fellow townsmen.
01Gn 34:21 "These men are friendly toward us," they said. "Let them live in our land and trade in it; the land has plenty of room for them. We can marry their daughters and they can marry ours.
01Gn 34:22 But the men will consent to live with us as one people only on the condition that our males be circumcised, as they themselves are.
01Gn 34:23 Won't their livestock, their property and all their other animals become ours? So let us give our consent to them, and they will settle among us."
01Gn 34:24 All the men who went out of the city gate agreed with Hamor and his son Shechem, and every male in the city was circumcised.
01Gn 34:25 Three days later, while all of them were still in pain, two of Jacob's sons, Simeon and Levi, Dinah's brothers, took their swords and attacked the unsuspecting city, killing every male.
01Gn 34:26 They put Hamor and his son Shechem to the sword and took Dinah from Shechem's house and left.
01Gn 34:27 The sons of Jacob came upon the dead bodies and looted the city where their sister had been defiled.
01Gn 34:28 They seized their flocks and herds and donkeys and everything else of theirs in the city and out in the fields.
01Gn 34:29 They carried off all their wealth and all their women and children, taking as plunder everything in the houses.
01Gn 34:30 Then Jacob said to Simeon and Levi, "You have brought trouble on me by making me a stench to the Canaanites and Perizzites, the people living in this land. We are few in number, and if they join forces against me and attack me, I and my household will be destroyed."
01Gn 34:31 But they replied, "Should he have treated our sister like a prostitute?"
01Gn 35:1 Then God said to Jacob, "Go up to Bethel and settle there, and build an altar there to God, who appeared to you when you were fleeing from your brother Esau."
01Gn 35:2 So Jacob said to his household and to all who were with him, "Get rid of the foreign gods you have with you, and purify yourselves and change your clothes.
01Gn 35:3 Then come, let us go up to Bethel, where I will build an altar to God, who answered me in the day of my distress and who has been with me wherever I have gone."
01Gn 35:4 So they gave Jacob all the foreign gods they had and the rings in their ears, and Jacob buried them under the oak at Shechem.
01Gn 35:5 Then they set out, and the terror of God fell upon the towns all around them so that no one pursued them.
01Gn 35:6 Jacob and all the people with him came to Luz (that is, Bethel) in the land of Canaan.
01Gn 35:7 There he built an altar, and he called the place El Bethel, because it was there that God revealed himself to him when he was fleeing from his brother.
01Gn 35:8 Now Deborah, Rebekah's nurse, died and was buried under the oak below Bethel. So it was named Allon Bacuth.
01Gn 35:9 After Jacob returned from Paddan Aram, God appeared to him again and blessed him.
01Gn 35:10 God said to him, "Your name is Jacob, but you will no longer be called Jacob; your name will be Israel." So he named him Israel.
01Gn 35:11 And God said to him, "I am God Almighty; be fruitful and increase in number. A nation and a community of nations will come from you, and kings will come from your body.
01Gn 35:12 The land I gave to Abraham and Isaac I also give to you, and I will give this land to your descendants after you."
01Gn 35:13 Then God went up from him at the place where he had talked with him.
01Gn 35:14 Jacob set up a stone pillar at the place where God had talked with him, and he poured out a drink offering on it; he also poured oil on it.
01Gn 35:15 Jacob called the place where God had talked with him Bethel.
01Gn 35:16 Then they moved on from Bethel. While they were still some distance from Ephrath, Rachel began to give birth and had great difficulty.
01Gn 35:17 And as she was having great difficulty in childbirth, the midwife said to her, "Don't be afraid, for you have another son."
01Gn 35:18 As she breathed her last--for she was dying--she named her son Ben-Oni. But his father named him Benjamin.
01Gn 35:19 So Rachel died and was buried on the way to Ephrath (that is, Bethlehem).
01Gn 35:20 Over her tomb Jacob set up a pillar, and to this day that pillar marks Rachel's tomb.
01Gn 35:21 Israel moved on again and pitched his tent beyond Migdal Eder.
01Gn 35:22 While Israel was living in that region, Reuben went in and slept with his father's concubine Bilhah, and Israel heard of it. Jacob had twelve sons£º
01Gn 35:23 The sons of Leah£º Reuben the firstborn of Jacob, Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar and Zebulun.
01Gn 35:24 The sons of Rachel£º Joseph and Benjamin.
01Gn 35:25 The sons of Rachel's maidservant Bilhah£º Dan and Naphtali.
01Gn 35:26 The sons of Leah's maidservant Zilpah£º Gad and Asher. These were the sons of Jacob, who were born to him in Paddan Aram.
01Gn 35:27 Jacob came home to his father Isaac in Mamre, near Kiriath Arba (that is, Hebron), where Abraham and Isaac had stayed.
01Gn 35:28 Isaac lived a hundred and eighty years.
01Gn 35:29 Then he breathed his last and died and was gathered to his people, old and full of years. And his sons Esau and Jacob buried him.
01Gn 36:1 This is the account of Esau (that is, Edom).
01Gn 36:2 Esau took his wives from the women of Canaan£º Adah daughter of Elon the Hittite, and Oholibamah daughter of Anah and granddaughter of Zibeon the Hivite--
01Gn 36:3 also Basemath daughter of Ishmael and sister of Nebaioth.
01Gn 36:4 Adah bore Eliphaz to Esau, Basemath bore Reuel,
01Gn 36:5 and Oholibamah bore Jeush, Jalam and Korah. These were the sons of Esau, who were born to him in Canaan.
01Gn 36:6 Esau took his wives and sons and daughters and all the members of his household, as well as his livestock and all his other animals and all the goods he had acquired in Canaan, and moved to a land some distance from his brother Jacob.
01Gn 36:7 Their possessions were too great for them to remain together; the land where they were staying could not support them both because of their livestock.
01Gn 36:8 So Esau (that is, Edom) settled in the hill country of Seir.
01Gn 36:9 This is the account of Esau the father of the Edomites in the hill country of Seir.
01Gn 36:10 These are the names of Esau's sons£º Eliphaz, the son of Esau's wife Adah, and Reuel, the son of Esau's wife Basemath.
01Gn 36:11 The sons of Eliphaz£º Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam and Kenaz.
01Gn 36:12 Esau's son Eliphaz also had a concubine named Timna, who bore him Amalek. These were grandsons of Esau's wife Adah.
01Gn 36:13 The sons of Reuel£º Nahath, Zerah, Shammah and Mizzah. These were grandsons of Esau's wife Basemath.
01Gn 36:14 The sons of Esau's wife Oholibamah daughter of Anah and granddaughter of Zibeon, whom she bore to Esau£º Jeush, Jalam and Korah.
01Gn 36:15 These were the chiefs among Esau's descendants£º The sons of Eliphaz the firstborn of Esau£º Chiefs Teman, Omar, Zepho, Kenaz,
01Gn 36:16 Korah, Gatam and Amalek. These were the chiefs descended from Eliphaz in Edom; they were grandsons of Adah.
01Gn 36:17 The sons of Esau's son Reuel£º Chiefs Nahath, Zerah, Shammah and Mizzah. These were the chiefs descended from Reuel in Edom; they were grandsons of Esau's wife Basemath.
01Gn 36:18 The sons of Esau's wife Oholibamah£º Chiefs Jeush, Jalam and Korah. These were the chiefs descended from Esau's wife Oholibamah daughter of Anah.
01Gn 36:19 These were the sons of Esau (that is, Edom), and these were their chiefs.
01Gn 36:20 These were the sons of Seir the Horite, who were living in the region£º Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah,
01Gn 36:21 Dishon, Ezer and Dishan. These sons of Seir in Edom were Horite chiefs.
01Gn 36:22 The sons of Lotan£º Hori and Homam. Timna was Lotan's sister.
01Gn 36:23 The sons of Shobal£º Alvan, Manahath, Ebal, Shepho and Onam.
01Gn 36:24 The sons of Zibeon£º Aiah and Anah. This is the Anah who discovered the hot springs in the desert while he was grazing the donkeys of his father Zibeon.
01Gn 36:25 The children of Anah£º Dishon and Oholibamah daughter of Anah.
01Gn 36:26 The sons of Dishon£º Hemdan, Eshban, Ithran and Keran.
01Gn 36:27 The sons of Ezer£º Bilhan, Zaavan and Akan.
01Gn 36:28 The sons of Dishan£º Uz and Aran.
01Gn 36:29 These were the Horite chiefs£º Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah,
01Gn 36:30 Dishon, Ezer and Dishan. These were the Horite chiefs, according to their divisions, in the land of Seir.
01Gn 36:31 These were the kings who reigned in Edom before any Israelite king reigned£º
01Gn 36:32 Bela son of Beor became king of Edom. His city was named Dinhabah.
01Gn 36:33 When Bela died, Jobab son of Zerah from Bozrah succeeded him as king.
01Gn 36:34 When Jobab died, Husham from the land of the Temanites succeeded him as king.
01Gn 36:35 When Husham died, Hadad son of Bedad, who defeated Midian in the country of Moab, succeeded him as king. His city was named Avith.
01Gn 36:36 When Hadad died, Samlah from Masrekah succeeded him as king.
01Gn 36:37 When Samlah died, Shaul from Rehoboth on the river succeeded him as king.
01Gn 36:38 When Shaul died, Baal-Hanan son of Acbor succeeded him as king.
01Gn 36:39 When Baal-Hanan son of Acbor died, Hadad succeeded him as king. His city was named Pau, and his wife's name was Mehetabel daughter of Matred, the daughter of Me-Zahab.
01Gn 36:40 These were the chiefs descended from Esau, by name, according to their clans and regions£º Timna, Alvah, Jetheth,
01Gn 36:41 Oholibamah, Elah, Pinon,
01Gn 36:42 Kenaz, Teman, Mibzar,
01Gn 36:43 Magdiel and Iram. These were the chiefs of Edom, according to their settlements in the land they occupied. This was Esau the father of the Edomites.
01Gn 37:1 Jacob lived in the land where his father had stayed, the land of Canaan.
01Gn 37:2 This is the account of Jacob. Joseph, a young man of seventeen, was tending the flocks with his brothers, the sons of Bilhah and the sons of Zilpah, his father's wives, and he brought their father a bad report about them.
01Gn 37:3 Now Israel loved Joseph more than any of his other sons, because he had been born to him in his old age; and he made a richly ornamented robe for him.
01Gn 37:4 When his brothers saw that their father loved him more than any of them, they hated him and could not speak a kind word to him.
01Gn 37:5 Joseph had a dream, and when he told it to his brothers, they hated him all the more.
01Gn 37:6 He said to them, "Listen to this dream I had£º
01Gn 37:7 We were binding sheaves of grain out in the field when suddenly my sheaf rose and stood upright, while your sheaves gathered around mine and bowed down to it."
01Gn 37:8 His brothers said to him, "Do you intend to reign over us? Will you actually rule us?" And they hated him all the more because of his dream and what he had said.
01Gn 37:9 Then he had another dream, and he told it to his brothers. "Listen," he said, "I had another dream, and this time the sun and moon and eleven stars were bowing down to me."
01Gn 37:10 When he told his father as well as his brothers, his father rebuked him and said, "What is this dream you had? Will your mother and I and your brothers actually come and bow down to the ground before you?"
01Gn 37:11 His brothers were jealous of him, but his father kept the matter in mind.
01Gn 37:12 Now his brothers had gone to graze their father's flocks near Shechem,
01Gn 37:13 and Israel said to Joseph, "As you know, your brothers are grazing the flocks near Shechem. Come, I am going to send you to them." "Very well," he replied.
01Gn 37:14 So he said to him, "Go and see if all is well with your brothers and with the flocks, and bring word back to me." Then he sent him off from the Valley of Hebron. When Joseph arrived at Shechem,
01Gn 37:15 a man found him wandering around in the fields and asked him, "What are you looking for?"
01Gn 37:16 He replied, "I'm looking for my brothers. Can you tell me where they are grazing their flocks?"
01Gn 37:17 "They have moved on from here," the man answered. "I heard them say, 'Let's go to Dothan.'" So Joseph went after his brothers and found them near Dothan.
01Gn 37:18 But they saw him in the distance, and before he reached them, they plotted to kill him.
01Gn 37:19 "Here comes that dreamer!" they said to each other.
01Gn 37:20 "Come now, let's kill him and throw him into one of these cisterns and say that a ferocious animal devoured him. Then we'll see what comes of his dreams."
01Gn 37:21 When Reuben heard this, he tried to rescue him from their hands. "Let's not take his life," he said.
01Gn 37:22 "Don't shed any blood. Throw him into this cistern here in the desert, but don't lay a hand on him." Reuben said this to rescue him from them and take him back to his father.
01Gn 37:23 So when Joseph came to his brothers, they stripped him of his robe--the richly ornamented robe he was wearing--
01Gn 37:24 and they took him and threw him into the cistern. Now the cistern was empty; there was no water in it.
01Gn 37:25 As they sat down to eat their meal, they looked up and saw a caravan of Ishmaelites coming from Gilead. Their camels were loaded with spices, balm and myrrh, and they were on their way to take them down to Egypt.
01Gn 37:26 Judah said to his brothers, "What will we gain if we kill our brother and cover up his blood?
01Gn 37:27 Come, let's sell him to the Ishmaelites and not lay our hands on him; after all, he is our brother, our own flesh and blood." His brothers agreed.
01Gn 37:28 So when the Midianite merchants came by, his brothers pulled Joseph up out of the cistern and sold him for twenty shekels of silver to the Ishmaelites, who took him to Egypt.
01Gn 37:29 When Reuben returned to the cistern and saw that Joseph was not there, he tore his clothes.
01Gn 37:30 He went back to his brothers and said, "The boy isn't there! Where can I turn now?"
01Gn 37:31 Then they got Joseph's robe, slaughtered a goat and dipped the robe in the blood.
01Gn 37:32 They took the ornamented robe back to their father and said, "We found this. Examine it to see whether it is your son's robe."
01Gn 37:33 He recognized it and said, "It is my son's robe! Some ferocious animal has devoured him. Joseph has surely been torn to pieces."
01Gn 37:34 Then Jacob tore his clothes, put on sackcloth and mourned for his son many days.
01Gn 37:35 All his sons and daughters came to comfort him, but he refused to be comforted. "No," he said, "in mourning will I go down to the grave to my son." So his father wept for him.
01Gn 37:36 Meanwhile, the Midianites sold Joseph in Egypt to Potiphar, one of Pharaoh's officials, the captain of the guard.
01Gn 38:1 At that time, Judah left his brothers and went down to stay with a man of Adullam named Hirah.
01Gn 38:2 There Judah met the daughter of a Canaanite man named Shua. He married her and lay with her;
01Gn 38:3 she became pregnant and gave birth to a son, who was named Er.
01Gn 38:4 She conceived again and gave birth to a son and named him Onan.
01Gn 38:5 She gave birth to still another son and named him Shelah. It was at Kezib that she gave birth to him.
01Gn 38:6 Judah got a wife for Er, his firstborn, and her name was Tamar.
01Gn 38:7 But Er, Judah's firstborn, was wicked in the LORD'S sight; so the LORD put him to death.
01Gn 38:8 Then Judah said to Onan, "Lie with your brother's wife and fulfill your duty to her as a brother-in-law to produce offspring for your brother."
01Gn 38:9 But Onan knew that the offspring would not be his; so whenever he lay with his brother's wife, he spilled his semen on the ground to keep from producing offspring for his brother.
01Gn 38:10 What he did was wicked in the LORD'S sight; so he put him to death also.
01Gn 38:11 Judah then said to his daughter-in-law Tamar, "Live as a widow in your father's house until my son Shelah grows up." For he thought, "He may die too, just like his brothers." So Tamar went to live in her father's house.
01Gn 38:12 After a long time Judah's wife, the daughter of Shua, died. When Judah had recovered from his grief, he went up to Timnah, to the men who were shearing his sheep, and his friend Hirah the Adullamite went with him.
01Gn 38:13 When Tamar was told, "Your father-in-law is on his way to Timnah to shear his sheep,"
01Gn 38:14 she took off her widow's clothes, covered herself with a veil to disguise herself, and then sat down at the entrance to Enaim, which is on the road to Timnah. For she saw that, though Shelah had now grown up, she had not been given to him as his wife.
01Gn 38:15 When Judah saw her, he thought she was a prostitute, for she had covered her face.
01Gn 38:16 Not realizing that she was his daughter-in-law, he went over to her by the roadside and said, "Come now, let me sleep with you." "And what will you give me to sleep with you?" she asked.
01Gn 38:17 "I'll send you a young goat from my flock," he said. "Will you give me something as a pledge until you send it?" she asked.
01Gn 38:18 He said, "What pledge should I give you?" "Your seal and its cord, and the staff in your hand," she answered. So he gave them to her and slept with her, and she became pregnant by him.
01Gn 38:19 After she left, she took off her veil and put on her widow's clothes again.
01Gn 38:20 Meanwhile Judah sent the young goat by his friend the Adullamite in order to get his pledge back from the woman, but he did not find her.
01Gn 38:21 He asked the men who lived there, "Where is the shrine prostitute who was beside the road at Enaim?" "There hasn't been any shrine prostitute here," they said.
01Gn 38:22 So he went back to Judah and said, "I didn't find her. Besides, the men who lived there said, 'There hasn't been any shrine prostitute here.'"
01Gn 38:23 Then Judah said, "Let her keep what she has, or we will become a laughingstock. After all, I did send her this young goat, but you didn't find her."
01Gn 38:24 About three months later Judah was told, "Your daughter-in-law Tamar is guilty of prostitution, and as a result she is now pregnant." Judah said, "Bring her out and have her burned to death!"
01Gn 38:25 As she was being brought out, she sent a message to her father-in-law. "I am pregnant by the man who owns these," she said. And she added, "See if you recognize whose seal and cord and staff these are."
01Gn 38:26 Judah recognized them and said, "She is more righteous than I, since I wouldn't give her to my son Shelah." And he did not sleep with her again.
01Gn 38:27 When the time came for her to give birth, there were twin boys in her womb.
01Gn 38:28 As she was giving birth, one of them put out his hand; so the midwife took a scarlet thread and tied it on his wrist and said, "This one came out first."
01Gn 38:29 But when he drew back his hand, his brother came out, and she said, "So this is how you have broken out!" And he was named Perez.
01Gn 38:30 Then his brother, who had the scarlet thread on his wrist, came out and he was given the name Zerah.
01Gn 39:1 Now Joseph had been taken down to Egypt. Potiphar, an Egyptian who was one of Pharaoh's officials, the captain of the guard, bought him from the Ishmaelites who had taken him there.
01Gn 39:2 The LORD was with Joseph and he prospered, and he lived in the house of his Egyptian master.
01Gn 39:3 When his master saw that the LORD was with him and that the LORD gave him success in everything he did,
01Gn 39:4 Joseph found favor in his eyes and became his attendant. Potiphar put him in charge of his household, and he entrusted to his care everything he owned.
01Gn 39:5 From the time he put him in charge of his household and of all that he owned, the LORD blessed the household of the Egyptian because of Joseph. The blessing of the LORD was on everything Potiphar had, both in the house and in the field.
01Gn 39:6 So he left in Joseph's care everything he had; with Joseph in charge, he did not concern himself with anything except the food he ate. Now Joseph was well-built and handsome,
01Gn 39:7 and after a while his master's wife took notice of Joseph and said, "Come to bed with me!"
01Gn 39:8 But he refused. "With me in charge," he told her, "my master does not concern himself with anything in the house; everything he owns he has entrusted to my care.
01Gn 39:9 No one is greater in this house than I am. My master has withheld nothing from me except you, because you are his wife. How then could I do such a wicked thing and sin against God?"
01Gn 39:10 And though she spoke to Joseph day after day, he refused to go to bed with her or even be with her.
01Gn 39:11 One day he went into the house to attend to his duties, and none of the household servants was inside.
01Gn 39:12 She caught him by his cloak and said, "Come to bed with me!" But he left his cloak in her hand and ran out of the house.
01Gn 39:13 When she saw that he had left his cloak in her hand and had run out of the house,
01Gn 39:14 she called her household servants. "Look," she said to them, "this Hebrew has been brought to us to make sport of us! He came in here to sleep with me, but I screamed.
01Gn 39:15 When he heard me scream for help, he left his cloak beside me and ran out of the house."
01Gn 39:16 She kept his cloak beside her until his master came home.
01Gn 39:17 Then she told him this story£º "That Hebrew slave you brought us came to me to make sport of me.
01Gn 39:18 But as soon as I screamed for help, he left his cloak beside me and ran out of the house."
01Gn 39:19 When his master heard the story his wife told him, saying, "This is how your slave treated me," he burned with anger.
01Gn 39:20 Joseph's master took him and put him in prison, the place where the king's prisoners were confined. But while Joseph was there in the prison,
01Gn 39:21 the LORD was with him; he showed him kindness and granted him favor in the eyes of the prison warden.
01Gn 39:22 So the warden put Joseph in charge of all those held in the prison, and he was made responsible for all that was done there.
01Gn 39:23 The warden paid no attention to anything under Joseph's care, because the LORD was with Joseph and gave him success in whatever he did.
01Gn 40:1 Some time later, the cupbearer and the baker of the king of Egypt offended their master, the king of Egypt.
01Gn 40:2 Pharaoh was angry with his two officials, the chief cupbearer and the chief baker,
01Gn 40:3 and put them in custody in the house of the captain of the guard, in the same prison where Joseph was confined.
01Gn 40:4 The captain of the guard assigned them to Joseph, and he attended them. After they had been in custody for some time,
01Gn 40:5 each of the two men--the cupbearer and the baker of the king of Egypt, who were being held in prison--had a dream the same night, and each dream had a meaning of its own.
01Gn 40:6 When Joseph came to them the next morning, he saw that they were dejected.
01Gn 40:7 So he asked Pharaoh's officials who were in custody with him in his master's house, "Why are your faces so sad today?"
01Gn 40:8 "We both had dreams," they answered, "but there is no one to interpret them." Then Joseph said to them, "Do not interpretations belong to God? Tell me your dreams."
01Gn 40:9 So the chief cupbearer told Joseph his dream. He said to him, "In my dream I saw a vine in front of me,
01Gn 40:10 and on the vine were three branches. As soon as it budded, it blossomed, and its clusters ripened into grapes.
01Gn 40:11 Pharaoh's cup was in my hand, and I took the grapes, squeezed them into Pharaoh's cup and put the cup in his hand."
01Gn 40:12 "This is what it means," Joseph said to him. "The three branches are three days.
01Gn 40:13 Within three days Pharaoh will lift up your head and restore you to your position, and you will put Pharaoh's cup in his hand, just as you used to do when you were his cupbearer.
01Gn 40:14 But when all goes well with you, remember me and show me kindness; mention me to Pharaoh and get me out of this prison.
01Gn 40:15 For I was forcibly carried off from the land of the Hebrews, and even here I have done nothing to deserve being put in a dungeon."
01Gn 40:16 When the chief baker saw that Joseph had given a favorable interpretation, he said to Joseph, "I too had a dream£º On my head were three baskets of bread.
01Gn 40:17 In the top basket were all kinds of baked goods for Pharaoh, but the birds were eating them out of the basket on my head."
01Gn 40:18 "This is what it means," Joseph said. "The three baskets are three days.
01Gn 40:19 Within three days Pharaoh will lift off your head and hang you on a tree. And the birds will eat away your flesh."
01Gn 40:20 Now the third day was Pharaoh's birthday, and he gave a feast for all his officials. He lifted up the heads of the chief cupbearer and the chief baker in the presence of his officials£º
01Gn 40:21 He restored the chief cupbearer to his position, so that he once again put the cup into Pharaoh's hand,
01Gn 40:22 but he hanged the chief baker, just as Joseph had said to them in his interpretation.
01Gn 40:23 The chief cupbearer, however, did not remember Joseph; he forgot him.
01Gn 41:1 When two full years had passed, Pharaoh had a dream£º He was standing by the Nile,
01Gn 41:2 when out of the river there came up seven cows, sleek and fat, and they grazed among the reeds.
01Gn 41:3 After them, seven other cows, ugly and gaunt, came up out of the Nile and stood beside those on the riverbank.
01Gn 41:4 And the cows that were ugly and gaunt ate up the seven sleek, fat cows. Then Pharaoh woke up.
01Gn 41:5 He fell asleep again and had a second dream£º Seven heads of grain, healthy and good, were growing on a single stalk.
01Gn 41:6 After them, seven other heads of grain sprouted--thin and scorched by the east wind.
01Gn 41:7 The thin heads of grain swallowed up the seven healthy, full heads. Then Pharaoh woke up; it had been a dream.
01Gn 41:8 In the morning his mind was troubled, so he sent for all the magicians and wise men of Egypt. Pharaoh told them his dreams, but no one could interpret them for him.
01Gn 41:9 Then the chief cupbearer said to Pharaoh, "Today I am reminded of my shortcomings.
01Gn 41:10 Pharaoh was once angry with his servants, and he imprisoned me and the chief baker in the house of the captain of the guard.
01Gn 41:11 Each of us had a dream the same night, and each dream had a meaning of its own.
01Gn 41:12 Now a young Hebrew was there with us, a servant of the captain of the guard. We told him our dreams, and he interpreted them for us, giving each man the interpretation of his dream.
01Gn 41:13 And things turned out exactly as he interpreted them to us£º I was restored to my position, and the other man was hanged."
01Gn 41:14 So Pharaoh sent for Joseph, and he was quickly brought from the dungeon. When he had shaved and changed his clothes, he came before Pharaoh.
01Gn 41:15 Pharaoh said to Joseph, "I had a dream, and no one can interpret it. But I have heard it said of you that when you hear a dream you can interpret it."
01Gn 41:16 "I cannot do it," Joseph replied to Pharaoh, "but God will give Pharaoh the answer he desires."
01Gn 41:17 Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, "In my dream I was standing on the bank of the Nile,
01Gn 41:18 when out of the river there came up seven cows, fat and sleek, and they grazed among the reeds.
01Gn 41:19 After them, seven other cows came up--scrawny and very ugly and lean. I had never seen such ugly cows in all the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:20 The lean, ugly cows ate up the seven fat cows that came up first.
01Gn 41:21 But even after they ate them, no one could tell that they had done so; they looked just as ugly as before. Then I woke up.
01Gn 41:22 "In my dreams I also saw seven heads of grain, full and good, growing on a single stalk.
01Gn 41:23 After them, seven other heads sprouted--withered and thin and scorched by the east wind.
01Gn 41:24 The thin heads of grain swallowed up the seven good heads. I told this to the magicians, but none could explain it to me."
01Gn 41:25 Then Joseph said to Pharaoh, "The dreams of Pharaoh are one and the same. God has revealed to Pharaoh what he is about to do.
01Gn 41:26 The seven good cows are seven years, and the seven good heads of grain are seven years; it is one and the same dream.
01Gn 41:27 The seven lean, ugly cows that came up afterward are seven years, and so are the seven worthless heads of grain scorched by the east wind£º They are seven years of famine.
01Gn 41:28 "It is just as I said to Pharaoh£º God has shown Pharaoh what he is about to do.
01Gn 41:29 Seven years of great abundance are coming throughout the land of Egypt,
01Gn 41:30 but seven years of famine will follow them. Then all the abundance in Egypt will be forgotten, and the famine will ravage the land.
01Gn 41:31 The abundance in the land will not be remembered, because the famine that follows it will be so severe.
01Gn 41:32 The reason the dream was given to Pharaoh in two forms is that the matter has been firmly decided by God, and God will do it soon.
01Gn 41:33 "And now let Pharaoh look for a discerning and wise man and put him in charge of the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:34 Let Pharaoh appoint commissioners over the land to take a fifth of the harvest of Egypt during the seven years of abundance.
01Gn 41:35 They should collect all the food of these good years that are coming and store up the grain under the authority of Pharaoh, to be kept in the cities for food.
01Gn 41:36 This food should be held in reserve for the country, to be used during the seven years of famine that will come upon Egypt, so that the country may not be ruined by the famine."
01Gn 41:37 The plan seemed good to Pharaoh and to all his officials.
01Gn 41:38 So Pharaoh asked them, "Can we find anyone like this man, one in whom is the spirit of God?"
01Gn 41:39 Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, "Since God has made all this known to you, there is no one so discerning and wise as you.
01Gn 41:40 You shall be in charge of my palace, and all my people are to submit to your orders. Only with respect to the throne will I be greater than you."
01Gn 41:41 So Pharaoh said to Joseph, "I hereby put you in charge of the whole land of Egypt."
01Gn 41:42 Then Pharaoh took his signet ring from his finger and put it on Joseph's finger. He dressed him in robes of fine linen and put a gold chain around his neck.
01Gn 41:43 He had him ride in a chariot as his second-in-command, and men shouted before him, "Make way!" Thus he put him in charge of the whole land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:44 Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, "I am Pharaoh, but without your word no one will lift hand or foot in all Egypt."
01Gn 41:45 Pharaoh gave Joseph the name Zaphenath-Paneah and gave him Asenath daughter of Potiphera, priest of On, to be his wife. And Joseph went throughout the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:46 Joseph was thirty years old when he entered the service of Pharaoh king of Egypt. And Joseph went out from Pharaoh's presence and traveled throughout Egypt.
01Gn 41:47 During the seven years of abundance the land produced plentifully.
01Gn 41:48 Joseph collected all the food produced in those seven years of abundance in Egypt and stored it in the cities. In each city he put the food grown in the fields surrounding it.
01Gn 41:49 Joseph stored up huge quantities of grain, like the sand of the sea; it was so much that he stopped keeping records because it was beyond measure.
01Gn 41:50 Before the years of famine came, two sons were born to Joseph by Asenath daughter of Potiphera, priest of On.
01Gn 41:51 Joseph named his firstborn Manasseh and said, "It is because God has made me forget all my trouble and all my father's household."
01Gn 41:52 The second son he named Ephraim and said, "It is because God has made me fruitful in the land of my suffering."
01Gn 41:53 The seven years of abundance in Egypt came to an end,
01Gn 41:54 and the seven years of famine began, just as Joseph had said. There was famine in all the other lands, but in the whole land of Egypt there was food.
01Gn 41:55 When all Egypt began to feel the famine, the people cried to Pharaoh for food. Then Pharaoh told all the Egyptians, "Go to Joseph and do what he tells you."
01Gn 41:56 When the famine had spread over the whole country, Joseph opened the storehouses and sold grain to the Egyptians, for the famine was severe throughout Egypt.
01Gn 41:57 And all the countries came to Egypt to buy grain from Joseph, because the famine was severe in all the world.
01Gn 42:1 When Jacob learned that there was grain in Egypt, he said to his sons, "Why do you just keep looking at each other?"
01Gn 42:2 He continued, "I have heard that there is grain in Egypt. Go down there and buy some for us, so that we may live and not die."
01Gn 42:3 Then ten of Joseph's brothers went down to buy grain from Egypt.
01Gn 42:4 But Jacob did not send Benjamin, Joseph's brother, with the others, because he was afraid that harm might come to him.
01Gn 42:5 So Israel's sons were among those who went to buy grain, for the famine was in the land of Canaan also.
01Gn 42:6 Now Joseph was the governor of the land, the one who sold grain to all its people. So when Joseph's brothers arrived, they bowed down to him with their faces to the ground.
01Gn 42:7 As soon as Joseph saw his brothers, he recognized them, but he pretended to be a stranger and spoke harshly to them. "Where do you come from?" he asked. "From the land of Canaan," they replied, "to buy food."
01Gn 42:8 Although Joseph recognized his brothers, they did not recognize him.
01Gn 42:9 Then he remembered his dreams about them and said to them, "You are spies! You have come to see where our land is unprotected."
01Gn 42:10 "No, my lord," they answered. "Your servants have come to buy food.
01Gn 42:11 We are all the sons of one man. Your servants are honest men, not spies."
01Gn 42:12 "No!" he said to them. "You have come to see where our land is unprotected."
01Gn 42:13 But they replied, "Your servants were twelve brothers, the sons of one man, who lives in the land of Canaan. The youngest is now with our father, and one is no more."
01Gn 42:14 Joseph said to them, "It is just as I told you£º You are spies!
01Gn 42:15 And this is how you will be tested£º As surely as Pharaoh lives, you will not leave this place unless your youngest brother comes here.
01Gn 42:16 Send one of your number to get your brother; the rest of you will be kept in prison, so that your words may be tested to see if you are telling the truth. If you are not, then as surely as Pharaoh lives, you are spies!"
01Gn 42:17 And he put them all in custody for three days.
01Gn 42:18 On the third day, Joseph said to them, "Do this and you will live, for I fear God£º
01Gn 42:19 If you are honest men, let one of your brothers stay here in prison, while the rest of you go and take grain back for your starving households.
01Gn 42:20 But you must bring your youngest brother to me, so that your words may be verified and that you may not die." This they proceeded to do.
01Gn 42:21 They said to one another, "Surely we are being punished because of our brother. We saw how distressed he was when he pleaded with us for his life, but we would not listen; that's why this distress has come upon us."
01Gn 42:22 Reuben replied, "Didn't I tell you not to sin against the boy? But you wouldn't listen! Now we must give an accounting for his blood."
01Gn 42:23 They did not realize that Joseph could understand them, since he was using an interpreter.
01Gn 42:24 He turned away from them and began to weep, but then turned back and spoke to them again. He had Simeon taken from them and bound before their eyes.
01Gn 42:25 Joseph gave orders to fill their bags with grain, to put each man's silver back in his sack, and to give them provisions for their journey. After this was done for them,
01Gn 42:26 they loaded their grain on their donkeys and left.
01Gn 42:27 At the place where they stopped for the night one of them opened his sack to get feed for his donkey, and he saw his silver in the mouth of his sack.
01Gn 42:28 "My silver has been returned," he said to his brothers. "Here it is in my sack." Their hearts sank and they turned to each other trembling and said, "What is this that God has done to us?"
01Gn 42:29 When they came to their father Jacob in the land of Canaan, they told him all that had happened to them. They said,
01Gn 42:30 "The man who is lord over the land spoke harshly to us and treated us as though we were spying on the land.
01Gn 42:31 But we said to him, 'We are honest men; we are not spies.
01Gn 42:32 We were twelve brothers, sons of one father. One is no more, and the youngest is now with our father in Canaan.'
01Gn 42:33 "Then the man who is lord over the land said to us, 'This is how I will know whether you are honest men£º Leave one of your brothers here with me, and take food for your starving households and go.
01Gn 42:34 But bring your youngest brother to me so I will know that you are not spies but honest men. Then I will give your brother back to you, and you can trade in the land.'"
01Gn 42:35 As they were emptying their sacks, there in each man's sack was his pouch of silver! When they and their father saw the money pouches, they were frightened.
01Gn 42:36 Their father Jacob said to them, "You have deprived me of my children. Joseph is no more and Simeon is no more, and now you want to take Benjamin. Everything is against me!"
01Gn 42:37 Then Reuben said to his father, "You may put both of my sons to death if I do not bring him back to you. Entrust him to my care, and I will bring him back."
01Gn 42:38 But Jacob said, "My son will not go down there with you; his brother is dead and he is the only one left. If harm comes to him on the journey you are taking, you will bring my gray head down to the grave in sorrow."
01Gn 43:1 Now the famine was still severe in the land.
01Gn 43:2 So when they had eaten all the grain they had brought from Egypt, their father said to them, "Go back and buy us a little more food."
01Gn 43:3 But Judah said to him, "The man warned us solemnly, 'You will not see my face again unless your brother is with you.'
01Gn 43:4 If you will send our brother along with us, we will go down and buy food for you.
01Gn 43:5 But if you will not send him, we will not go down, because the man said to us, 'You will not see my face again unless your brother is with you.'"
01Gn 43:6 Israel asked, "Why did you bring this trouble on me by telling the man you had another brother?"
01Gn 43:7 They replied, "The man questioned us closely about ourselves and our family. 'Is your father still living?' he asked us. 'Do you have another brother?' We simply answered his questions. How were we to know he would say, 'Bring your brother down here'?"
01Gn 43:8 Then Judah said to Israel his father, "Send the boy along with me and we will go at once, so that we and you and our children may live and not die.
01Gn 43:9 I myself will guarantee his safety; you can hold me personally responsible for him. If I do not bring him back to you and set him here before you, I will bear the blame before you all my life.
01Gn 43:10 As it is, if we had not delayed, we could have gone and returned twice."
01Gn 43:11 Then their father Israel said to them, "If it must be, then do this£º Put some of the best products of the land in your bags and take them down to the man as a gift--a little balm and a little honey, some spices and myrrh, some pistachio nuts and almonds.
01Gn 43:12 Take double the amount of silver with you, for you must return the silver that was put back into the mouths of your sacks. Perhaps it was a mistake.
01Gn 43:13 Take your brother also and go back to the man at once.
01Gn 43:14 And may God Almighty grant you mercy before the man so that he will let your other brother and Benjamin come back with you. As for me, if I am bereaved, I am bereaved."
01Gn 43:15 So the men took the gifts and double the amount of silver, and Benjamin also. They hurried down to Egypt and presented themselves to Joseph.
01Gn 43:16 When Joseph saw Benjamin with them, he said to the steward of his house, "Take these men to my house, slaughter an animal and prepare dinner; they are to eat with me at noon."
01Gn 43:17 The man did as Joseph told him and took the men to Joseph's house.
01Gn 43:18 Now the men were frightened when they were taken to his house. They thought, "We were brought here because of the silver that was put back into our sacks the first time. He wants to attack us and overpower us and seize us as slaves and take our donkeys."
01Gn 43:19 So they went up to Joseph's steward and spoke to him at the entrance to the house.
01Gn 43:20 "Please, sir," they said, "we came down here the first time to buy food.
01Gn 43:21 But at the place where we stopped for the night we opened our sacks and each of us found his silver--the exact weight--in the mouth of his sack. So we have brought it back with us.
01Gn 43:22 We have also brought additional silver with us to buy food. We don't know who put our silver in our sacks."
01Gn 43:23 "It's all right," he said. "Don't be afraid. Your God, the God of your father, has given you treasure in your sacks; I received your silver." Then he brought Simeon out to them.
01Gn 43:24 The steward took the men into Joseph's house, gave them water to wash their feet and provided fodder for their donkeys.
01Gn 43:25 They prepared their gifts for Joseph's arrival at noon, because they had heard that they were to eat there.
01Gn 43:26 When Joseph came home, they presented to him the gifts they had brought into the house, and they bowed down before him to the ground.
01Gn 43:27 He asked them how they were, and then he said, "How is your aged father you told me about? Is he still living?"
01Gn 43:28 They replied, "Your servant our father is still alive and well." And they bowed low to pay him honor.
01Gn 43:29 As he looked about and saw his brother Benjamin, his own mother's son, he asked, "Is this your youngest brother, the one you told me about?" And he said, "God be gracious to you, my son."
01Gn 43:30 Deeply moved at the sight of his brother, Joseph hurried out and looked for a place to weep. He went into his private room and wept there.
01Gn 43:31 After he had washed his face, he came out and, controlling himself, said, "Serve the food."
